{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T13:53:21.954930", "agent_name": "AstroDeepResearchAgent", "method_name": "load_cached_research", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "Cached research loaded from: deep_research_gpt5.4/Threonine-Run1.txt", "user_message": "Config: deep_research_gpt5.4", "raw_response": "Prebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] https://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\nhttps://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\n[4] [5] [9] [11] [15] [17] [18] [24] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\n[7] [12] REACTIONS OF AMINOMALONONITRILE WITH ... - HERO\nhttps://hero.epa.gov/reference/10713764/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n[10] [19] [23] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\n[13] [14] [16] https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\nhttps://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\n[20] [21] https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\nhttps://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\n[22] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\n", "parsed_response": {"source": "deep_research_gpt5.4/Threonine-Run1.txt", "config": "deep_research_gpt5.4", "length": 19075}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 0.0, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T13:53:21.956049", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Threonine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] https://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\nhttps://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\n[4] [5] [9] [11] [15] [17] [18] [24] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\n[7] [12] REACTIONS OF AMINOMALONONITRILE WITH ... - HERO\nhttps://hero.epa.gov/reference/10713764/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n[10] [19] [23] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\n[13] [14] [16] https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\nhttps://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\n[20] [21] https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\nhttps://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\n[22] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network is centered on the literature-supported lactaldehyde -> threonine aminonitrile -> threonine module, with multiple convergent upstream routes supplying lactaldehyde, HCN, NH3, and related C/N feedstocks. Hydrothermal chemistry contributes reductants, carbonyl precursors, cyanide-conditioning, and limited Strecker-style processing under mineral-buffered conditions, while surface photochemistry and discharge chemistry generate the key aldehyde/nitrile intermediates. Final conversion to threonine occurs through Strecker aminonitrile formation followed by hydrolysis, with parallel alternative AMN-based and discharge-derived routes included where experimentally supported. The design explicitly reflects the literature constraint that threonine is generally formed together with allothreonine and that hydroxy-amino-acid survival is less favorable under prolonged hydrothermal heating.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h2,4H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H5NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-3(5)2-4/h3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"propanedial, 2-amino-2,2-dicarbonitrile derivative\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminomalononitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2N2Fe4(CN)6\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"iron(II) hexacyanidoferrate(II) salt ensemble\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ferrocyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"sulfane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde from CO2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor hydrothermal reducing conditions; serpentinization-associated H2 supply\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-catalyzed CO2 hydrogenation under reducing hydrothermal conditions generates reduced one-carbon carbonyl feedstocks, represented here by formaldehyde as a surface-exportable precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included as a connective hydrothermal carbon-fixation module consistent with iron- and magnetite-mediated CO2 reduction/Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry described in hydrothermal origin-of-life frameworks; used here only to supply upstream carbonyl inventory feeding surface HCN chemistry. This step is more general than threonine-specific and is therefore partly connective/speculative. It is constrained by hydrothermal mineral chemistry summarized by Andersson & Holm (2000) and by the contrast with failed direct CO2-to-amino-acid claims in Keefe et al. (1995), so the product is treated as a precursor pool rather than direct amino-acid synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic-plume spark discharge production of HCN and NH3 feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"localized high-energy discharge; bulk collection at 300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile), sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"atmospheric/volcanic plume discharge products wash out into surface waters; reducing gas mixtures analogous to CH4/NH3/H2S/CO2 systems\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge in reducing volcanic-plume analog atmospheres forms reactive C-N species, especially HCN and ammonia-bearing products, which accumulate in surface waters for downstream Strecker and photoredox chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Supported by classic discharge syntheses and reanalysis showing threonine among amino acid products and interpreting plume/discharge chemistry as generating HCN and related precursors that rain out into tidal settings (Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011). Mineral agents are included to satisfy the surface-mineral requirement and to reflect adsorption/photochemical concentration in shoreline settings, though the core transformation is discharge-driven rather than mineral-catalyzed.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanohydrin formation from formaldehyde and HCN to glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite), TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide-rich surface pool; pre-photoredox feedstock assembly\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic cyanide addition to formaldehyde yields glycolonitrile, establishing the nitrile node used in cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolonitrile is the direct upstream substrate used in the Ritson-Sutherland network, where HCN-derived nitriles feed UV photoredox reduction sequences toward aldehydes and amino-acid precursors (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021). This condensation is a necessary connector to the experimentally studied photoredox step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"CuCN/H2S UV photoredox reduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient; 300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN photoredox system generated from copper sulfide mineral dissolution in cyanide solution; H2S as terminal reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H2S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, solid CuCN 10 mol%, 254 nm UV, quartz cuvette, 2 h; glycolaldehyde formed in 42% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanide photoredox cycling generates hydrated-electron chemistry that reduces nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes, yielding glycolaldehyde from glycolonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly based on the quantitatively specified cyanosulfidic photoredox conditions of Ritson & Sutherland (2013), with systems-level support from Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021). The mineral field here reflects the paper's geochemical bridge from copper sulfides and FeS dissolution to CuCN and H2S supply.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoredox side-production of acetaldehyde from glycolonitrile-derived UV network\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient; 300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN photoredox system generated from copper sulfide mineral dissolution in cyanide solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"same network context as 254 nm irradiation of glycolonitrile/H2S/phosphate/CuCN; acetaldehyde reported among aldehydic products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The same UV photoredox network that reduces glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde also furnishes acetaldehyde as a downstream/side aldehydic product, creating a branch into acetaldehyde-derived threonine precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013) explicitly note acetaldehyde among aldehydic products formed during glycolonitrile photoreduction, and Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021) situate these aldehyde nodes in a broader cyanosulfidic network. This provides one experimentally anchored entry into the acetaldehyde/lactaldehyde branch.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin from acetaldehyde and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite), montmorillonite (clay)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide-rich evaporitic or geothermal pool; precursor to second-stage photoreduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN to generate the dedicated cyanohydrin node that photoreduces to lactaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is required because Ritson & Sutherland (2013) explicitly identify irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin as the source of lactaldehyde, the carbonyl precursor to (allo-)threonine. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin analysis likewise treats carbonyl/cyanohydrin interconversion as central to amino-acid production (Shimoyama et al.-type discussion summarized in the Kyushu report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Second-stage UV photoredox reduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient; 300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN photoredox system generated from copper sulfide mineral dissolution in cyanide solution; H2S as terminal reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"254 nm UV irradiation for 2 h; lactaldehyde formed in 19% yield from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven cyanocuprate photoredox reduction of the cyanohydrin furnishes lactaldehyde, the key aldehyde-level threonine precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the core literature-defined threonine-precursor step: Ritson & Sutherland (2013) directly report 19% lactaldehyde from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin after 2 h irradiation and identify lactaldehyde as the Strecker precursor to (allo-)threonine; Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021) restate this node in the larger cyanosulfidic systems framework.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay), sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN-rich concentrated pools; oligomerization/accumulation step with competition from polymerization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomerization generates multifunctional C/N oligomers, represented here by aminomalononitrile as an alternative threonine-precursor synthon.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thanassi (1975) identifies aminomalononitrile chemistry as a route to threonine/allothreonine after electrophile reaction and hydrolysis, while Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021) discuss HCN oligomer chemistry and its challenges. This node is included as the literature-supported alternative C-N assembly branch.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker conversion of lactaldehyde to threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentration on sulfide minerals and clays; cyanide/ammonia-rich aqueous setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"days to weeks holding time after addition of HCN and NH3 to photoreduction products; via cyanohydrin/iminium-Strecker sequence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde forms an imine/iminium with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to generate the aminonitrile Strecker intermediate corresponding to threonine/allothreonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013) explicitly state that adding HCN and NH3 to photoreduction products smoothly converts lactaldehyde via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile; Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021) place this in a broader UV-cyanosulfidic network; the meteoritic Strecker analysis also identifies lactaldehyde as the threonine carbonyl precursor.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN plus lactaldehyde route to threonine aminonitrile-equivalent precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay), phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous conditions followed by hydrolytic workup; represented here as convergence onto the same threonine-directed nitrile intermediate pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminomalononitrile reacts with aldehydic electrophiles to generate hydrolysis-competent amino-nitrile precursors leading to threonine/allothreonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thanassi (1975) experimentally showed that aminomalononitrile reactions with electrophiles including aldehydes followed by hydrolysis yield threonine and allothreonine. Because the exact discrete intermediate set is not fully standardized in the report, this node is represented as convergence into the threonine-directed aminonitrile pool; this is the least structurally explicit but literature-supported branch.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools or during alteration; produces threonine/allothreonine mixture\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Classical aminonitrile hydrolysis converts the nitrile to a carboxylic acid, yielding threonine as the amino-acid product of the Strecker module.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the standard final step of Strecker frameworks and is explicitly described in the meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussion for alpha-amino acids, including threonine from lactaldehyde-derived intermediates (Kyushu report; also implicit in Ritson & Sutherland, 2013). Diastereomeric threonine/allothreonine production is expected.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal ferrocyanide conditioning and reagent release to HCN/NH3 pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS), pyrite (FeS2)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fe2+-rich anoxic waters; cyanide concentration by iron complexation; later thermal processing/rehydration can regenerate cyanide/ammonia-bearing reagent mixtures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced iron sulfide settings condition cyanide through ferrocyanide-type complexation, acting as a concentrator/reservoir that can subsequently feed surface cyanide-ammonia chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2013) specifically discuss ferrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and note that thermal processing of ferrocyanide salts can yield cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration. This reaction is included as a literature-grounded Hydrothermal -> Surface bridge, not as direct threonine synthesis.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic photoredox route from hydrothermal carbon to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon reduction supplies formaldehyde; surface cyanide chemistry forms glycolonitrile; UV photoredox generates glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde, then acetaldehyde cyanohydrin photoreduces to lactaldehyde, which undergoes Strecker conversion and hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Discharge-fed glycolonitrile branch to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Volcanic-plume discharge supplies HCN/NH3 that combine with formaldehyde to glycolonitrile, then proceed through the UV photoredox acetaldehyde/lactaldehyde branch to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoredox lactaldehyde route with explicit glycolaldehyde node\",\n      \"description\": \"This route emphasizes the Ritson-Sutherland first-stage glycolonitrile reduction to glycolaldehyde as part of the same network before branching to acetaldehyde and then lactaldehyde-derived Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetaldehyde cyanohydrin direct photoreduction route\",\n      \"description\": \"Once acetaldehyde is available from the surface photoredox network, cyanohydrin formation followed by second-stage UV reduction provides a compact route to lactaldehyde and onward to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Lactaldehyde-centered Strecker module\",\n      \"description\": \"Minimal experimentally grounded threonine module using lactaldehyde as the dedicated carbonyl precursor and HCN/NH3 as Strecker reagents, followed by hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN electrophile route to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN oligomerization supplies aminomalononitrile, which reacts with aldehydic electrophile equivalents and converges into threonine-directed nitrile precursors before hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN plus lactaldehyde convergent route\",\n      \"description\": \"The HCN oligomer branch and the cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde branch converge when AMN reacts with lactaldehyde-derived electrophile chemistry to produce threonine-forming nitrile intermediates.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal ferrocyanide conditioning to surface Strecker-threonine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal iron-sulfide settings condition cyanide/ammonia into ferrocyanide-type reservoirs that later feed surface HCN/NH3 chemistry, enabling the lactaldehyde Strecker route to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Discharge-to-lactaldehyde-to-threonine pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"This pathway highlights atmospheric/plume chemistry as the key supplier of HCN/NH3, followed by acetaldehyde cyanohydrin formation, photoreduction to lactaldehyde, and Strecker hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Integrated hydrothermal-surface-biochemical network to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"The full cross-environment network begins with hydrothermal reduced-carbon and ferrocyanide conditioning, moves through surface cyanide and cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry to lactaldehyde and/or AMN-derived nitrile intermediates, then ends with biochemical aqueous hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "The network is centered on the literature-supported lactaldehyde -> threonine aminonitrile -> threonine module, with multiple convergent upstream routes supplying lactaldehyde, HCN, NH3, and related C/N feedstocks. Hydrothermal chemistry contributes reductants, carbonyl precursors, cyanide-conditioning, and limited Strecker-style processing under mineral-buffered conditions, while surface photochemistry and discharge chemistry generate the key aldehyde/nitrile intermediates. Final conversion to threonine occurs through Strecker aminonitrile formation followed by hydrolysis, with parallel alternative AMN-based and discharge-derived routes included where experimentally supported. The design explicitly reflects the literature constraint that threonine is generally formed together with allothreonine and that hydroxy-amino-acid survival is less favorable under prolonged hydrothermal heating.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h2,4H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "acetaldehyde cyanohydrin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-3(5)2-4/h3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H4N2", "iupac_name": "propanedial, 2-amino-2,2-dicarbonitrile derivative", "common_name": "aminomalononitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "CH2N2Fe4(CN)6", "iupac_name": "iron(II) hexacyanidoferrate(II) salt ensemble", "common_name": "ferrocyanide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde from CO2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal reducing conditions; serpentinization-associated H2 supply"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed CO2 hydrogenation under reducing hydrothermal conditions generates reduced one-carbon carbonyl feedstocks, represented here by formaldehyde as a surface-exportable precursor.", "reasoning": "Included as a connective hydrothermal carbon-fixation module consistent with iron- and magnetite-mediated CO2 reduction/Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry described in hydrothermal origin-of-life frameworks; used here only to supply upstream carbonyl inventory feeding surface HCN chemistry. This step is more general than threonine-specific and is therefore partly connective/speculative. It is constrained by hydrothermal mineral chemistry summarized by Andersson & Holm (2000) and by the contrast with failed direct CO2-to-amino-acid claims in Keefe et al. (1995), so the product is treated as a precursor pool rather than direct amino-acid synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Volcanic-plume spark discharge production of HCN and NH3 feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "localized high-energy discharge; bulk collection at 300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile), sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "atmospheric/volcanic plume discharge products wash out into surface waters; reducing gas mixtures analogous to CH4/NH3/H2S/CO2 systems"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge in reducing volcanic-plume analog atmospheres forms reactive C-N species, especially HCN and ammonia-bearing products, which accumulate in surface waters for downstream Strecker and photoredox chemistry.", "reasoning": "Supported by classic discharge syntheses and reanalysis showing threonine among amino acid products and interpreting plume/discharge chemistry as generating HCN and related precursors that rain out into tidal settings (Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011). Mineral agents are included to satisfy the surface-mineral requirement and to reflect adsorption/photochemical concentration in shoreline settings, though the core transformation is discharge-driven rather than mineral-catalyzed."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface cyanohydrin formation from formaldehyde and HCN to glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite), TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanide-rich surface pool; pre-photoredox feedstock assembly"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic cyanide addition to formaldehyde yields glycolonitrile, establishing the nitrile node used in cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry.", "reasoning": "Glycolonitrile is the direct upstream substrate used in the Ritson-Sutherland network, where HCN-derived nitriles feed UV photoredox reduction sequences toward aldehydes and amino-acid precursors (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021). This condensation is a necessary connector to the experimentally studied photoredox step."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "CuCN/H2S UV photoredox reduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient; 300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN photoredox system generated from copper sulfide mineral dissolution in cyanide solution; H2S as terminal reductant", "aqueous": "true", "other": "10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H2S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, solid CuCN 10 mol%, 254 nm UV, quartz cuvette, 2 h; glycolaldehyde formed in 42% yield"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanide photoredox cycling generates hydrated-electron chemistry that reduces nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes, yielding glycolaldehyde from glycolonitrile.", "reasoning": "Directly based on the quantitatively specified cyanosulfidic photoredox conditions of Ritson & Sutherland (2013), with systems-level support from Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021). The mineral field here reflects the paper's geochemical bridge from copper sulfides and FeS dissolution to CuCN and H2S supply."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Photoredox side-production of acetaldehyde from glycolonitrile-derived UV network", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient; 300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN photoredox system generated from copper sulfide mineral dissolution in cyanide solution", "aqueous": "true", "other": "same network context as 254 nm irradiation of glycolonitrile/H2S/phosphate/CuCN; acetaldehyde reported among aldehydic products"}, "mechanism": "The same UV photoredox network that reduces glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde also furnishes acetaldehyde as a downstream/side aldehydic product, creating a branch into acetaldehyde-derived threonine precursors.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013) explicitly note acetaldehyde among aldehydic products formed during glycolonitrile photoreduction, and Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021) situate these aldehyde nodes in a broader cyanosulfidic network. This provides one experimentally anchored entry into the acetaldehyde/lactaldehyde branch."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Formation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin from acetaldehyde and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite), montmorillonite (clay)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanide-rich evaporitic or geothermal pool; precursor to second-stage photoreduction"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN to generate the dedicated cyanohydrin node that photoreduces to lactaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This step is required because Ritson & Sutherland (2013) explicitly identify irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin as the source of lactaldehyde, the carbonyl precursor to (allo-)threonine. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin analysis likewise treats carbonyl/cyanohydrin interconversion as central to amino-acid production (Shimoyama et al.-type discussion summarized in the Kyushu report)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Second-stage UV photoredox reduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient; 300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN photoredox system generated from copper sulfide mineral dissolution in cyanide solution; H2S as terminal reductant", "aqueous": "true", "other": "254 nm UV irradiation for 2 h; lactaldehyde formed in 19% yield from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven cyanocuprate photoredox reduction of the cyanohydrin furnishes lactaldehyde, the key aldehyde-level threonine precursor.", "reasoning": "This is the core literature-defined threonine-precursor step: Ritson & Sutherland (2013) directly report 19% lactaldehyde from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin after 2 h irradiation and identify lactaldehyde as the Strecker precursor to (allo-)threonine; Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021) restate this node in the larger cyanosulfidic systems framework."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay), sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN-rich concentrated pools; oligomerization/accumulation step with competition from polymerization"}, "mechanism": "HCN oligomerization generates multifunctional C/N oligomers, represented here by aminomalononitrile as an alternative threonine-precursor synthon.", "reasoning": "Thanassi (1975) identifies aminomalononitrile chemistry as a route to threonine/allothreonine after electrophile reaction and hydrolysis, while Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021) discuss HCN oligomer chemistry and its challenges. This node is included as the literature-supported alternative C-N assembly branch."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Strecker conversion of lactaldehyde to threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface concentration on sulfide minerals and clays; cyanide/ammonia-rich aqueous setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "days to weeks holding time after addition of HCN and NH3 to photoreduction products; via cyanohydrin/iminium-Strecker sequence"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde forms an imine/iminium with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to generate the aminonitrile Strecker intermediate corresponding to threonine/allothreonine.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013) explicitly state that adding HCN and NH3 to photoreduction products smoothly converts lactaldehyde via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile; Green, Xu & Sutherland (2021) place this in a broader UV-cyanosulfidic network; the meteoritic Strecker analysis also identifies lactaldehyde as the threonine carbonyl precursor."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "AMN plus lactaldehyde route to threonine aminonitrile-equivalent precursor pool", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay), phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous conditions followed by hydrolytic workup; represented here as convergence onto the same threonine-directed nitrile intermediate pool"}, "mechanism": "Aminomalononitrile reacts with aldehydic electrophiles to generate hydrolysis-competent amino-nitrile precursors leading to threonine/allothreonine.", "reasoning": "Thanassi (1975) experimentally showed that aminomalononitrile reactions with electrophiles including aldehydes followed by hydrolysis yield threonine and allothreonine. Because the exact discrete intermediate set is not fully standardized in the report, this node is represented as convergence into the threonine-directed aminonitrile pool; this is the least structurally explicit but literature-supported branch."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools or during alteration; produces threonine/allothreonine mixture"}, "mechanism": "Classical aminonitrile hydrolysis converts the nitrile to a carboxylic acid, yielding threonine as the amino-acid product of the Strecker module.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the standard final step of Strecker frameworks and is explicitly described in the meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussion for alpha-amino acids, including threonine from lactaldehyde-derived intermediates (Kyushu report; also implicit in Ritson & Sutherland, 2013). Diastereomeric threonine/allothreonine production is expected."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrothermal ferrocyanide conditioning and reagent release to HCN/NH3 pool", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS), pyrite (FeS2)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fe2+-rich anoxic waters; cyanide concentration by iron complexation; later thermal processing/rehydration can regenerate cyanide/ammonia-bearing reagent mixtures"}, "mechanism": "Reduced iron sulfide settings condition cyanide through ferrocyanide-type complexation, acting as a concentrator/reservoir that can subsequently feed surface cyanide-ammonia chemistry.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2013) specifically discuss ferrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and note that thermal processing of ferrocyanide salts can yield cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration. This reaction is included as a literature-grounded Hydrothermal -> Surface bridge, not as direct threonine synthesis."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical cyanosulfidic photoredox route from hydrothermal carbon to threonine", "description": "Hydrothermal carbon reduction supplies formaldehyde; surface cyanide chemistry forms glycolonitrile; UV photoredox generates glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde, then acetaldehyde cyanohydrin photoreduces to lactaldehyde, which undergoes Strecker conversion and hydrolysis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Discharge-fed glycolonitrile branch to threonine", "description": "Volcanic-plume discharge supplies HCN/NH3 that combine with formaldehyde to glycolonitrile, then proceed through the UV photoredox acetaldehyde/lactaldehyde branch to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Photoredox lactaldehyde route with explicit glycolaldehyde node", "description": "This route emphasizes the Ritson-Sutherland first-stage glycolonitrile reduction to glycolaldehyde as part of the same network before branching to acetaldehyde and then lactaldehyde-derived Strecker synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Acetaldehyde cyanohydrin direct photoreduction route", "description": "Once acetaldehyde is available from the surface photoredox network, cyanohydrin formation followed by second-stage UV reduction provides a compact route to lactaldehyde and onward to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Lactaldehyde-centered Strecker module", "description": "Minimal experimentally grounded threonine module using lactaldehyde as the dedicated carbonyl precursor and HCN/NH3 as Strecker reagents, followed by hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "AMN electrophile route to threonine", "description": "HCN oligomerization supplies aminomalononitrile, which reacts with aldehydic electrophile equivalents and converges into threonine-directed nitrile precursors before hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "AMN plus lactaldehyde convergent route", "description": "The HCN oligomer branch and the cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde branch converge when AMN reacts with lactaldehyde-derived electrophile chemistry to produce threonine-forming nitrile intermediates.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal ferrocyanide conditioning to surface Strecker-threonine route", "description": "Hydrothermal iron-sulfide settings condition cyanide/ammonia into ferrocyanide-type reservoirs that later feed surface HCN/NH3 chemistry, enabling the lactaldehyde Strecker route to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_012", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Discharge-to-lactaldehyde-to-threonine pathway", "description": "This pathway highlights atmospheric/plume chemistry as the key supplier of HCN/NH3, followed by acetaldehyde cyanohydrin formation, photoreduction to lactaldehyde, and Strecker hydrolysis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Integrated hydrothermal-surface-biochemical network to threonine", "description": "The full cross-environment network begins with hydrothermal reduced-carbon and ferrocyanide conditioning, moves through surface cyanide and cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry to lactaldehyde and/or AMN-derived nitrile intermediates, then ends with biochemical aqueous hydrolysis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_012", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_014", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_012"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_003", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_012"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_003", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_011"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 114031.0549736023, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T13:55:15.994308", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: The network is centered on the literature-supported lactaldehyde -> threonine aminonitrile -> threonine module, with multiple convergent upstream routes supplying lactaldehyde, HCN, NH3, and related C/N feedstocks. Hydrothermal chemistry contributes reductants, carbonyl precursors, cyanide-conditioning, and limited Strecker-style processing under mineral-buffered conditions, while surface photochemistry and discharge chemistry generate the key aldehyde/nitrile intermediates. Final conversion to threonine occurs through Strecker aminonitrile formation followed by hydrolysis, with parallel alternative AMN-based and discharge-derived routes included where experimentally supported. The design explicitly reflects the literature constraint that threonine is generally formed together with allothreonine and that hydroxy-amino-acid survival is less favorable under prolonged hydrothermal heating.\n\nMOLECULES (15 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: NH3 (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C2H3NO (glycolonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C3H5NO (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C3H6O2 (lactaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C3H4N2 (aminomalononitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C4H8N2O (threonine aminonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C4H9NO3 (threonine) [target]\n  - mol_014: CH2N2Fe4(CN)6 (ferrocyanide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n\nREACTIONS (12 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_005 (Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde from CO2) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_015 -> mol_003, mol_004 (Volcanic-plume spark discharge production of HCN and NH3 feedstocks) [Surface]\n  - rxn_003: mol_005, mol_003 -> mol_006 (Surface cyanohydrin formation from formaldehyde and HCN to glycolonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_004: mol_006, mol_015 -> mol_007 (CuCN/H2S UV photoredox reduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_006, mol_015 -> mol_008 (Photoredox side-production of acetaldehyde from glycolonitrile-derived UV network) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_008, mol_003 -> mol_009 (Formation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin from acetaldehyde and HCN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_009, mol_015 -> mol_010 (Second-stage UV photoredox reduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_003 -> mol_011 (HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_010, mol_003, mol_004 -> mol_012 (Strecker conversion of lactaldehyde to threonine aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_011, mol_010 -> mol_012 (AMN plus lactaldehyde route to threonine aminonitrile-equivalent precursor pool) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_012 -> mol_013 (Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_012: mol_003, mol_004 -> mol_014 (Hydrothermal ferrocyanide conditioning and reagent release to HCN/NH3 pool) [Hydrothermal]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Canonical cyanosulfidic photoredox route from hydrothermal carbon to threonine (9 steps)\n  - P2: Discharge-fed glycolonitrile branch to threonine (7 steps)\n  - P3: Photoredox lactaldehyde route with explicit glycolaldehyde node (7 steps)\n  - P4: Acetaldehyde cyanohydrin direct photoreduction route (5 steps)\n  - P5: Lactaldehyde-centered Strecker module (2 steps)\n  - P6: AMN electrophile route to threonine (3 steps)\n  - P7: AMN plus lactaldehyde convergent route (4 steps)\n  - P8: Hydrothermal ferrocyanide conditioning to surface Strecker-threonine route (5 steps)\n  - P9: Discharge-to-lactaldehyde-to-threonine pathway (5 steps)\n  - P10: Integrated hydrothermal-surface-biochemical network to threonine (9 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_003, mol_006, mol_008, mol_010, mol_012\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 4\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] https://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\nhttps://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\n[4] [5] [9] [11] [15] [17] [18] [24] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\n[7] [12] REACTIONS OF AMINOMALONONITRILE WITH ... - HERO\nhttps://hero.epa.gov/reference/10713764/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n[10] [19] [23] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\n[13] [14] [16] https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\nhttps://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\n[20] [21] https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\nhttps://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\n[22] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"approved\": <true if any pathway approved>,\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.32,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.96,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.87,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the strongest pathway because it matches the literature-centered cyanosulfidic route: glycolonitrile photoreduction to glycolaldehyde/acetaldehyde, acetaldehyde cyanohydrin photoreduction to lactaldehyde, then Strecker conversion to threonine aminonitrile and hydrolysis to threonine. The major weakness is the opening hydrothermal CO2-to-formaldehyde step, which is much less directly supported than the downstream UV photoredox and Strecker chemistry. Despite that upstream issue, the core lactaldehyde-centered threonine module is well aligned with Ritson-Sutherland and later systems work, and the final target is credibly achieved.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_001\",\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Replace or weaken rxn_001 as a specific formaldehyde-generating hydrothermal claim; literature support is stronger for discharge or photochemical generation of carbonyl precursors than direct vent production of formaldehyde from CO2.\",\n        \"Clarify that rxn_002 is a feedstock-generation analogue to discharge/plume chemistry rather than a single-step stoichiometric conversion from CO2 and H2S only.\",\n        \"Explicitly note threonine/allothreonine co-production in rxn_009 and rxn_011 to better match the literature.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.96,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"This discharge-fed branch is literature-consistent in spirit because spark discharge is empirically associated with HCN, NH3, aldehydes, and ultimately threonine/allothreonine production. It then hands off to a strong surface cyanosulfidic sequence and the standard aminonitrile hydrolysis endpoint. The main flaw is that the discharge node is oversimplified and under-specified chemically, but the route as a whole is plausible and connected.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Represent spark discharge as generating a mixture of reduced C/N species rather than direct clean conversion from CO2 and H2S to HCN and NH3.\",\n        \"Include a clearer source for formaldehyde if this pathway relies on rxn_003 after discharge feedstock generation.\",\n        \"State that this route likely yields mixed diastereomers rather than threonine alone.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.96,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.92,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.93,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.94,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.91,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the best-defined chemistry in the network. It closely follows the experimentally supported UV cyanosulfidic sequence in which glycolonitrile photoreduction gives glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde, acetaldehyde cyanohydrin gives lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde undergoes Strecker conversion to the threonine aminonitrile prior to hydrolysis. This pathway is strongly coherent, environmentally appropriate for a UV-exposed surface setting, and well aligned with the literature.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Specify that CuCN and phosphate are the key mineral/solution agents for rxn_004 and rxn_007, because these are central to the literature support.\",\n        \"Add that hydrolysis of the aminonitrile is plausible but less directly specified under the same photoredox conditions, so environmental transfer to milder aqueous processing should be made explicit.\",\n        \"Note expected co-production of allothreonine.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.93,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.95,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.92,\n      \"feedback\": \"This direct acetaldehyde-cyanohydrin photoreduction route is highly literature-aligned and captures the core threonine module with minimal speculative baggage. Acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde is explicitly reported, and lactaldehyde to threonine aminonitrile is the key documented Strecker step. The only limitation is that it assumes acetaldehyde availability upstream, but as an internal module it is excellent.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Strengthen the pathway by documenting a specific upstream acetaldehyde source in the same environment.\",\n        \"Mention that the aminonitrile product is specifically the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile mixture.\",\n        \"Clarify hydrolysis conditions for conversion to free threonine.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.9,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.96,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.86,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n      \"feedback\": \"The lactaldehyde-centered Strecker module is exactly the key mechanistic core identified in the literature. It is concise, chemically plausible, and directly reaches threonine through a standard aminonitrile intermediate. Its weakness is not internal chemistry but dependence on external supply of lactaldehyde under plausible prebiotic concentrations.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Annotate explicitly that this module generates threonine plus allothreonine in abiotic mixtures.\",\n        \"State that ammonia abundance is a critical branch control favoring aminonitrile formation over competing cyanohydrin persistence.\",\n        \"Link this module to better-supported lactaldehyde-generating upstream steps.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.61,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.73,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n      \"feedback\": \"The AMN route is literature-supported in general, since aminomalononitrile can react with aldehydes and after hydrolysis yield threonine/allothreonine. However, the specific representation here is weaker than the Strecker branch because rxn_010 collapses a more complex AMN-electrophile chemistry into a single poorly specified step and labels the product as the same threonine aminonitrile node, which is probably an oversimplification. This pathway is plausible but less rigorous.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Separate the AMN-lactaldehyde adduct from the canonical Strecker threonine aminonitrile node unless there is direct evidence they are identical.\",\n        \"Include a distinct hydrolysis or rearrangement step supported by Thanassi-type chemistry.\",\n        \"Acknowledge that AMN accumulation and selectivity are major unresolved prebiotic issues.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.61,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.76,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.75,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.83,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.83,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n      \"feedback\": \"This convergent AMN-plus-lactaldehyde pathway has good conceptual design because it merges two literature-supported branches. Yet the decisive C-N bond-forming step remains too underspecified. The network correctly identifies AMN as an alternative threonine precursor route, but the mapping onto the same aminonitrile intermediate used in the Strecker sequence reduces mechanistic clarity.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Use a distinct intermediate node for the AMN-derived precursor rather than merging it immediately with the Strecker aminonitrile.\",\n        \"Add hydrolysis details and literature-specific conditions for the AMN branch.\",\n        \"Preserve the distinction between canonical Strecker chemistry and AMN electrophile chemistry.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.91,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is a good cross-environment pathway because it uses ferrocyanide as a cyanide-conditioning reservoir before surface photochemistry and Strecker assembly. That feature aligns with the literature discussion of ferrocyanide concentration and thermal release of cyanide/ammonia equivalents. The concern is that rxn_012 is represented as a direct conversion to ferrocyanide without the necessary iron context and release chemistry, so it is more of a reservoir concept than a complete reaction.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add Fe2+ or an iron mineral explicitly to rxn_012 and distinguish ferrocyanide formation from later thermal release/rehydration chemistry.\",\n        \"Clarify whether ferrocyanide is a storage node or an active reagent source for downstream HCN/NH3.\",\n        \"Retain the strong downstream lactaldehyde-Strecker sequence, which is the best-supported part.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.89,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is viable if one accepts discharge/plume chemistry as the source of acetaldehyde/HCN/NH3-like precursors, followed by the highly plausible photoreduction and Strecker module. It is weaker than the best pathways because the discharge source is abstracted too far and may not explicitly furnish the required acetaldehyde node in the network. Still, its general environmental logic is consistent with the literature.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"sug