011": 0.84}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.73, "pathway_coherence": 0.72, "environmental_progression": 0.8, "target_achievement": 0.82, "overall_confidence": 0.76, "feedback": "The AMN route is literature-supported in general, since aminomalononitrile can react with aldehydes and after hydrolysis yield threonine/allothreonine. However, the specific representation here is weaker than the Strecker branch because rxn_010 collapses a more complex AMN-electrophile chemistry into a single poorly specified step and labels the product as the same threonine aminonitrile node, which is probably an oversimplification. This pathway is plausible but less rigorous.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_010"], "suggestions": ["Separate the AMN-lactaldehyde adduct from the canonical Strecker threonine aminonitrile node unless there is direct evidence they are identical.", "Include a distinct hydrolysis or rearrangement step supported by Thanassi-type chemistry.", "Acknowledge that AMN accumulation and selectivity are major unresolved prebiotic issues."]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_008": 0.88, "rxn_007": 0.97, "rxn_010": 0.61, "rxn_011": 0.84}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.76, "pathway_coherence": 0.75, "environmental_progression": 0.83, "target_achievement": 0.83, "overall_confidence": 0.78, "feedback": "This convergent AMN-plus-lactaldehyde pathway has good conceptual design because it merges two literature-supported branches. Yet the decisive C-N bond-forming step remains too underspecified. The network correctly identifies AMN as an alternative threonine precursor route, but the mapping onto the same aminonitrile intermediate used in the Strecker sequence reduces mechanistic clarity.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_010"], "suggestions": ["Use a distinct intermediate node for the AMN-derived precursor rather than merging it immediately with the Strecker aminonitrile.", "Add hydrolysis details and literature-specific conditions for the AMN branch.", "Preserve the distinction between canonical Strecker chemistry and AMN electrophile chemistry."]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_012": 0.68, "rxn_003": 0.94, "rxn_005": 0.86, "rxn_006": 0.95, "rxn_007": 0.97, "rxn_009": 0.95, "rxn_011": 0.84}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.84, "pathway_coherence": 0.84, "environmental_progression": 0.91, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.85, "feedback": "This is a good cross-environment pathway because it uses ferrocyanide as a cyanide-conditioning reservoir before surface photochemistry and Strecker assembly. That feature aligns with the literature discussion of ferrocyanide concentration and thermal release of cyanide/ammonia equivalents. The concern is that rxn_012 is represented as a direct conversion to ferrocyanide without the necessary iron context and release chemistry, so it is more of a reservoir concept than a complete reaction.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_012"], "suggestions": ["Add Fe2+ or an iron mineral explicitly to rxn_012 and distinguish ferrocyanide formation from later thermal release/rehydration chemistry.", "Clarify whether ferrocyanide is a storage node or an active reagent source for downstream HCN/NH3.", "Retain the strong downstream lactaldehyde-Strecker sequence, which is the best-supported part."]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.58, "rxn_006": 0.95, "rxn_007": 0.97, "rxn_009": 0.95, "rxn_011": 0.84}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.82, "pathway_coherence": 0.84, "environmental_progression": 0.89, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.84, "feedback": "This pathway is viable if one accepts discharge/plume chemistry as the source of acetaldehyde/HCN/NH3-like precursors, followed by the highly plausible photoreduction and Strecker module. It is weaker than the best pathways because the discharge source is abstracted too far and may not explicitly furnish the required acetaldehyde node in the network. Still, its general environmental logic is consistent with the literature.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "suggestions": ["Make the discharge branch produce a broader precursor pool including aldehydes explicitly.", "Avoid presenting spark discharge as a clean two-product reaction.", "Note that threonine would likely be part of a broader amino acid mixture rather than a selective endpoint."]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.32, "rxn_012": 0.68, "rxn_003": 0.94, "rxn_004": 0.96, "rxn_005": 0.86, "rxn_006": 0.95, "rxn_007": 0.97, "rxn_009": 0.95, "rxn_011": 0.84}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.8, "pathway_coherence": 0.89, "environmental_progression": 0.95, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.86, "feedback": "As a whole-network route, this is strong on integration: hydrothermal feedstock conditioning, surface UV chemistry, and final biochemical hydrolysis are connected coherently. It satisfies the requested environmental interconnection well. However, the hydrothermal opening reactions are the least secure chemically and are not the strongest literature-supported source of threonine precursors. The network succeeds overall because its downstream surface and biochemical steps are much better grounded.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_001", "rxn_012"], "suggestions": ["Downgrade direct hydrothermal formaldehyde production from a core route to a speculative auxiliary feeder pathway.", "Refine ferrocyanide handling as storage/release chemistry with explicit iron species and release conditions.", "Emphasize that hydrothermal settings are more credible as feedstock-conditioning environments than as the site of final threonine synthesis and persistence."]}], "best_pathway_id": "P4", "overall_confidence": 0.87, "network_feedback": "This is a good to very good synthesis network overall. Its main strength is that it correctly centers threonine synthesis on the literature-supported lactaldehyde -> threonine aminonitrile -> threonine module, and it builds sensible convergent upstream routes through glycolonitrile, acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, HCN, and NH3. The strongest parts are the UV cyanosulfidic surface reactions, which align closely with Ritson and Sutherland and later systems-level treatments, and the final Strecker/hydrolysis logic is sound. The network also appropriately reflects the literature caveat that abiotic synthesis should give threonine together with allothreonine and that hydroxy amino acids are vulnerable to degradation under hydrothermal heating. Topologically, the network is connected, has adequate size, and contains several real hubs and convergence points. The main weaknesses are in the hydrothermal feedstock steps: direct CO2 -> formaldehyde is under-supported in the provided threonine-specific literature, and the ferrocyanide conditioning step is more conceptually right than chemically complete as written. The AMN branch is a legitimate alternative but is compressed too aggressively into the same aminonitrile node used for the canonical Strecker pathway. Mineral-agent compliance is mixed: surface photoredox chemistry implicitly needs CuCN/phosphate and sulfide sources, while the summary as provided does not clearly document all required mineral agents for every non-biochemical reaction. Despite these issues, the network meets target achievement and literature alignment well enough to be considered approved.", "approved": true, "hub_quality": 0.88, "convergence_quality": 0.9}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 74187.34622001648, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T13:56:30.191662", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Threonine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] https://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\nhttps://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\n[4] [5] [9] [11] [15] [17] [18] [24] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\n[7] [12] REACTIONS OF AMINOMALONONITRILE WITH ... - HERO\nhttps://hero.epa.gov/reference/10713764/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n[10] [19] [23] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\n[13] [14] [16] https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\nhttps://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\n[20] [21] https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\nhttps://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\n[22] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.87\n- Feedback: This is a good to very good synthesis network overall. Its main strength is that it correctly centers threonine synthesis on the literature-supported lactaldehyde -> threonine aminonitrile -> threonine module, and it builds sensible convergent upstream routes through glycolonitrile, acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, HCN, and NH3. The strongest parts are the UV cyanosulfidic surface reactions, which align closely with Ritson and Sutherland and later systems-level treatments, and the final Strecker/hydrolysis logic is sound. The network also appropriately reflects the literature caveat that abiotic synthesis should give threonine together with allothreonine and that hydroxy amino acids are vulnerable to degradation under hydrothermal heating. Topologically, the network is connected, has adequate size, and contains several real hubs and convergence points. The main weaknesses are in the hydrothermal feedstock steps: direct CO2 -> formaldehyde is under-supported in the provided threonine-specific literature, and the ferrocyanide conditioning step is more conceptually right than chemically complete as written. The AMN branch is a legitimate alternative but is compressed too aggressively into the same aminonitrile node used for the canonical Strecker pathway. Mineral-agent compliance is mixed: surface photoredox chemistry implicitly needs CuCN/phosphate and sulfide sources, while the summary as provided does not clearly document all required mineral agents for every non-biochemical reaction. Despite these issues, the network meets target achievement and literature alignment well enough to be considered approved.\n- Issues: ['The AMN route is literature-supported in general, since aminomalononitrile can react with aldehydes and after hydrolysis yield threonine/allothreonine. However, the specific representation here is weaker than the Strecker branch because rxn_010 collapses a more complex AMN-electrophile chemistry into a single poorly specified step and labels the product as the same threonine aminonitrile node, which is probably an oversimplification. This pathway is plausible but less rigorous.', 'This convergent AMN-plus-lactaldehyde pathway has good conceptual design because it merges two literature-supported branches. Yet the decisive C-N bond-forming step remains too underspecified. The network correctly identifies AMN as an alternative threonine precursor route, but the mapping onto the same aminonitrile intermediate used in the Strecker sequence reduces mechanistic clarity.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network is centered on the literature-supported lactaldehyde -> threonine/allothreonine aminonitrile -> threonine module. Upstream convergence is built from (i) UV cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry that converts glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde under CuCN/H2S/phosphate conditions, (ii) spark-discharge atmospheric/plume chemistry that supplies HCN, NH3, aldehydes, and directly low levels of threonine/allothreonine, (iii) HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile followed by aldehyde capture and hydrolysis as an alternative C-N assembly route, and (iv) hydrothermal redox-buffered Strecker-style feedstock generation and hydrolysis that can support aminonitrile formation if lactaldehyde is available, while acknowledging the instability of hydroxy amino acids at elevated temperature. Ten distinct pathways are represented as different connected routes through shared hubs. Key hubs are HCN, NH3, lactaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"sulfane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h2,4H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H5NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-3(5)2-4/h3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,2-diaminomalononitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminomalononitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4N4/c4-1-3(7)2-5/h7H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)2-4(5)6/h3-4,7H,2,5H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"allothreonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic-plume spark discharge generation of HCN and NH3 feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"high-energy discharge, local plume heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide mineral surfaces as atmospheric/aerosol deposition substrates\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"spark-discharge in reducing volcanic-plume style gas mixtures containing CH4, NH3 or N2 traces, H2S, CO2; rainout to surface waters\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge generates radical and ionic intermediates in reduced gas mixtures, producing cyanide and aldehydes that are deposited into surface settings.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Spark-discharge experiments and their reanalysis show threonine-bearing product suites and imply formation of HCN, NH3, and aldehydes/ketones as precursor pools in volcanic-plume settings; Parker et al. 2011 and Ring et al. 1972 support this precursor-generating framework. Mineral agents are included here as surface deposition/photoactive minerals required by the schema, although the discharge chemistry itself is atmospheric rather than mineral-catalyzed. (Parker et al., 2011; Ring et al., 1972)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydration to formamide under UV-active surface conditions\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed evaporitic or geothermal pool; hydration and concentration during wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN is trapped and hydrated in sunlit surface waters to form a more persistent C-N reservoir that can feed downstream cyanide chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature emphasizes cyanide concentration/conditioning and UV-active surface chemistry as part of cyanosulfidic prebiotic networks; this step is a conservative connector to hold cyanide in surface pools and is used here to connect atmospheric input to downstream HCN-derived chemistry. It is more weakly direct than the lactaldehyde module and is included as a necessary network-connecting step, explicitly marked as a systems-level extrapolation from cyanide handling rather than a threonine-specific demonstrated transformation. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-derived formation of glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed aqueous pool with concentrated cyanide inventory\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-derived C1/CN chemistry gives glycolonitrile, a canonical nitrile node entering cyanosulfidic photoredox reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolonitrile is the explicit substrate for the first-stage Ritson-Sutherland photoreduction network and therefore must be included as a key upstream nitrile node. This reaction is included to connect the cyanide pool to that experimentally demonstrated substrate; the exact prebiotic route to glycolonitrile is not the threonine-specific focus of the report, so this connection is a necessary but somewhat schematic upstream condensation step. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient, 300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN generated from sulfide mineral dissolution in cyanide solution; sodium phosphate buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H2S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, solid CuCN at 10 mol%, 254 nm irradiation, quartz vessel, 2 h; glycolaldehyde observed in 42% yield with acetaldehyde among aldehydic products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox cycling of Cu(I) cyanide with sulfide-derived reducing equivalents produces hydrated-electron chemistry that reduces nitrile nodes to aldehydes.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a directly reported threonine-relevant upstream reaction: glycolonitrile photoreduction under CuCN/H2S/phosphate/254 nm conditions yields glycolaldehyde and other aldehydes including acetaldehyde. The mineral connection via sulfide-derived CuCN generation is explicit in the literature. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from acetaldehyde and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonia-poor to moderate-ammonia aqueous settings favor cyanohydrin capture; wet-dry concentration can assist\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to acetaldehyde forms the corresponding cyanohydrin, the direct photoreduction substrate for lactaldehyde production.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research specifically identifies acetaldehyde cyanohydrin as the immediate photoredox precursor to lactaldehyde in the Ritson-Sutherland sequence and notes ammonia abundance as a branch control between cyanohydrins and aminonitriles. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Kyushu meteoritic Strecker analysis)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient, 300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"CuCN generated from sulfide mineral dissolution in cyanide solution; phosphate buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"254 nm irradiation for 2 h; lactaldehyde reported in 19% yield from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin photoreduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CuCN-mediated UV photoredox reduction converts the cyanohydrin node into the aldehyde-level Strecker precursor lactaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key literature-defined dedicated threonine carbonyl-precursor step: second-stage cyanohydrin photoreduction gives lactaldehyde, explicitly identified as the precursor of (allo-)threonine. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrating pools with repeated evaporation and rehydration; oligomerization competes with polymerization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentrated HCN undergoes oligomerization to multifunctional aminonitrile-rich species, including aminomalononitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminomalononitrile is a key HCN oligomer discussed as an alternative C-N assembly route to threonine/allothreonine after reaction with electrophiles and hydrolysis. The literature notes plausibility alongside selectivity and accumulation challenges. (Thanassi, 1975; Green et al., 2021)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker assembly from lactaldehyde to threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"addition of HCN and NH3 to photoreduction products; aminonitrile formation over days to weeks; via imine/cyanohydrin-mediated Strecker sequence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine/iminium equivalent, followed by cyanide addition to give the threonine/allothreonine aminonitrile mixture.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the core module supported across the report: lactaldehyde is explicitly the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine, and Ritson-Sutherland report smooth conversion to the Strecker intermediate aminonitrile on addition of HCN and NH3. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021; Kyushu meteoritic Strecker analysis)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN-electrophile route: aminomalononitrile capture of lactaldehyde to threonine-family nitrile precursor\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous conditions; aldehyde electrophile capture followed by network-internal hydrolytic rearrangement to threonine-family aminonitrile precursor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminomalononitrile acts as a multifunctional C-N synthon, adding to aldehydic electrophiles and channeling carbon and nitrogen into threonine/allothreonine precursor space through a route distinct from canonical one-carbonyl Strecker assembly.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is intentionally separated from the canonical Strecker step to address the prior compression problem. Thanassi 1975 supports AMN plus aldehydes leading, after hydrolysis, to threonine/allothreonine, but the detailed intermediate structure is less explicitly resolved than for the lactaldehyde Strecker branch. Therefore this node is represented as converging on the experimentally relevant threonine-family aminonitrile space while acknowledging partial mechanistic compression. This is literature-supported but less specific than rxn_008. (Thanassi, 1975)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine and allothreonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prolonged aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools or during wet-dry/geothermal cycling; expected to yield diastereomeric threonine and allothreonine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide/carboxyl equivalents to the alpha-amino acid products, preserving the expected threonine/allothreonine diastereomeric outcome.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to alpha-amino acids is the standard terminal step of Strecker-type synthesis and is explicitly framed in meteoritic Strecker discussions. The report also emphasizes that abiotic syntheses typically generate threonine together with allothreonine. (Kyushu meteoritic Strecker analysis; Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Ring et al., 1972)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct spark-discharge production of threonine and allothreonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"high-energy discharge, local plume heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide mineral deposition surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing or locally reducing discharge system; product residues accumulate and wash into surface waters; threonine present at low abundance relative to glycine and largely racemic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex atmospheric radical chemistry followed by aqueous post-processing yields a suite of amino acids directly, including threonine and allothreonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Both Parker et al. 2011 and Ring et al. 1972 report threonine in spark-discharge residues, with Ring et al. explicitly confirming both threonine and allothreonine. This direct route is included as an experimentally grounded alternative path to the target, while also returning HCN and aldehyde feedstocks to the connected network. Mineral agents are again interpreted as environmental deposition/concentration surfaces to satisfy the schema. (Parker et al., 2011; Ring et al., 1972)\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal redox-buffered Strecker-style support and hydrolysis route to threonine from imported lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite\", \"magnetite\", \"mackinawite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"423K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"10 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite style redox buffer represented here by pyrite, magnetite, and FeS/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydrothermal Strecker-type conditions modeled on HCN/aldehyde/NH4+ experiments; included as a constrained route because threonine itself was not explicitly reported and hydroxy amino acids may degrade\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"If lactaldehyde is delivered into hydrothermal flank settings, redox-buffered Strecker aminonitrile formation and partial hydrolysis can occur, but product persistence is limited by hydrothermal degradation of hydroxy amino acids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is experimentally documented for several amino acids under 150 C and 10 bar with pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite buffers, but threonine was not explicitly tabulated; therefore this route is included only as a literature-constrained extension requiring imported lactaldehyde and explicitly acknowledging instability/degradation of hydroxy amino acids. It should be regarded as plausible but less directly demonstrated than the surface lactaldehyde route. (Andersson & Holm, 2000 summarizing Hennet et al., 1992; Bada et al., 1978; Keefe et al., 1995)\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic threonine pathway from atmospheric cyanide\",\n      \"description\": \"Spark-discharge feedstocks supply cyanide and acetaldehyde; acetaldehyde cyanohydrin is photoreduced to lactaldehyde, then Strecker assembly gives threonine aminonitrile and hydrolysis gives threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolonitrile-first photoredox pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Atmospheric cyanide is converted to glycolonitrile, photoreduced to glycolaldehyde plus acetaldehyde, then passes through cyanohydrin and lactaldehyde to threonine aminonitrile and threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct spark-discharge threonine synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"High-energy atmospheric discharge directly generates threonine and allothreonine in complex amino-acid mixtures.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN alternative route from atmospheric cyanide to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Atmospheric cyanide oligomerizes to aminomalononitrile; independently generated lactaldehyde is captured by AMN-derived chemistry and hydrolyzed to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hybrid discharge-photoredox route via direct acetaldehyde supply\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde from discharge chemistry enters the cyanohydrin-photoreduction sequence without requiring the glycolonitrile branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hybrid discharge-photoredox route with HCN conditioning through formamide\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is held in surface reservoirs as formamide-linked cyanide chemistry before entering glycolonitrile photoredox chemistry and then the lactaldehyde Strecker module.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomer route merged with canonical lactaldehyde module\",\n      \"description\": \"An HCN-rich pool simultaneously supports AMN formation and the canonical lactaldehyde Strecker route, yielding threonine through an alternative C-N assembly entry point.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal completion from surface-generated lactaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface photochemistry generates lactaldehyde, which is transported into hydrothermal flank settings where redox-buffered Strecker chemistry and hydrolysis can produce threonine, though with degradation risk.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolonitrile-to-hydrothermal hybrid pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"The full surface glycolonitrile photoredox sequence generates lactaldehyde, which then feeds a hydrothermal redox-buffered Strecker/hydrolysis step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface network with parallel direct and indirect threonine production\",\n      \"description\": \"A single plume-fed environment can yield some threonine directly by discharge while also building a larger threonine pool indirectly through the lactaldehyde aminonitrile route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "The network is centered on the literature-supported lactaldehyde -> threonine/allothreonine aminonitrile -> threonine module. Upstream convergence is built from (i) UV cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry that converts glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde under CuCN/H2S/phosphate conditions, (ii) spark-discharge atmospheric/plume chemistry that supplies HCN, NH3, aldehydes, and directly low levels of threonine/allothreonine, (iii) HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile followed by aldehyde capture and hydrolysis as an alternative C-N assembly route, and (iv) hydrothermal redox-buffered Strecker-style feedstock generation and hydrolysis that can support aminonitrile formation if lactaldehyde is available, while acknowledging the instability of hydroxy amino acids at elevated temperature. Ten distinct pathways are represented as different connected routes through shared hubs. Key hubs are HCN, NH3, lactaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h2,4H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "acetaldehyde cyanohydrin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-3(5)2-4/h3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H4N4", "iupac_name": "2,2-diaminomalononitrile", "common_name": "aminomalononitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4N4/c4-1-3(7)2-5/h7H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)2-4(5)6/h3-4,7H,2,5H2,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "allothreonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Volcanic-plume spark discharge generation of HCN and NH3 feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "high-energy discharge, local plume heating", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide mineral surfaces as atmospheric/aerosol deposition substrates", "aqueous": "false", "other": "spark-discharge in reducing volcanic-plume style gas mixtures containing CH4, NH3 or N2 traces, H2S, CO2; rainout to surface waters"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge generates radical and ionic intermediates in reduced gas mixtures, producing cyanide and aldehydes that are deposited into surface settings.", "reasoning": "Spark-discharge experiments and their reanalysis show threonine-bearing product suites and imply formation of HCN, NH3, and aldehydes/ketones as precursor pools in volcanic-plume settings; Parker et al. 2011 and Ring et al. 1972 support this precursor-generating framework. Mineral agents are included here as surface deposition/photoactive minerals required by the schema, although the discharge chemistry itself is atmospheric rather than mineral-catalyzed. (Parker et al., 2011; Ring et al., 1972)"}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "HCN hydration to formamide under UV-active surface conditions", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed evaporitic or geothermal pool; hydration and concentration during wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "HCN is trapped and hydrated in sunlit surface waters to form a more persistent C-N reservoir that can feed downstream cyanide chemistry.", "reasoning": "The literature emphasizes cyanide concentration/conditioning and UV-active surface chemistry as part of cyanosulfidic prebiotic networks; this step is a conservative connector to hold cyanide in surface pools and is used here to connect atmospheric input to downstream HCN-derived chemistry. It is more weakly direct than the lactaldehyde module and is included as a necessary network-connecting step, explicitly marked as a systems-level extrapolation from cyanide handling rather than a threonine-specific demonstrated transformation. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021)"}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "HCN-derived formation of glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed aqueous pool with concentrated cyanide inventory"}, "mechanism": "HCN-derived C1/CN chemistry gives glycolonitrile, a canonical nitrile node entering cyanosulfidic photoredox reduction.", "reasoning": "Glycolonitrile is the explicit substrate for the first-stage Ritson-Sutherland photoreduction network and therefore must be included as a key upstream nitrile node. This reaction is included to connect the cyanide pool to that experimentally demonstrated substrate; the exact prebiotic route to glycolonitrile is not the threonine-specific focus of the report, so this connection is a necessary but somewhat schematic upstream condensation step. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021)"}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient, 300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN generated from sulfide mineral dissolution in cyanide solution; sodium phosphate buffer", "aqueous": "true", "other": "10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H2S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, solid CuCN at 10 mol%, 254 nm irradiation, quartz vessel, 2 h; glycolaldehyde observed in 42% yield with acetaldehyde among aldehydic products"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox cycling of Cu(I) cyanide with sulfide-derived reducing equivalents produces hydrated-electron chemistry that reduces nitrile nodes to aldehydes.", "reasoning": "This is a directly reported threonine-relevant upstream reaction: glycolonitrile photoreduction under CuCN/H2S/phosphate/254 nm conditions yields glycolaldehyde and other aldehydes including acetaldehyde. The mineral connection via sulfide-derived CuCN generation is explicit in the literature. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021)"}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation from acetaldehyde and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonia-poor to moderate-ammonia aqueous settings favor cyanohydrin capture; wet-dry concentration can assist"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to acetaldehyde forms the corresponding cyanohydrin, the direct photoreduction substrate for lactaldehyde production.", "reasoning": "The deep research specifically identifies acetaldehyde cyanohydrin as the immediate photoredox precursor to lactaldehyde in the Ritson-Sutherland sequence and notes ammonia abundance as a branch control between cyanohydrins and aminonitriles. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Kyushu meteoritic Strecker analysis)"}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "UV cyanosulfidic photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient, 300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "CuCN generated from sulfide mineral dissolution in cyanide solution; phosphate buffer", "aqueous": "true", "other": "254 nm irradiation for 2 h; lactaldehyde reported in 19% yield from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin photoreduction"}, "mechanism": "CuCN-mediated UV photoredox reduction converts the cyanohydrin node into the aldehyde-level Strecker precursor lactaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the key literature-defined dedicated threonine carbonyl-precursor step: second-stage cyanohydrin photoreduction gives lactaldehyde, explicitly identified as the precursor of (allo-)threonine. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021)"}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "HCN oligomerization to aminomalononitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrating pools with repeated evaporation and rehydration; oligomerization competes with polymerization"}, "mechanism": "Concentrated HCN undergoes oligomerization to multifunctional aminonitrile-rich species, including aminomalononitrile.", "reasoning": "Aminomalononitrile is a key HCN oligomer discussed as an alternative C-N assembly route to threonine/allothreonine after reaction with electrophiles and hydrolysis. The literature notes plausibility alongside selectivity and accumulation challenges. (Thanassi, 1975; Green et al., 2021)"}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Strecker assembly from lactaldehyde to threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "addition of HCN and NH3 to photoreduction products; aminonitrile formation over days to weeks; via imine/cyanohydrin-mediated Strecker sequence"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine/iminium equivalent, followed by cyanide addition to give the threonine/allothreonine aminonitrile mixture.", "reasoning": "This is the core module supported across the report: lactaldehyde is explicitly the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine, and Ritson-Sutherland report smooth conversion to the Strecker intermediate aminonitrile on addition of HCN and NH3. (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021; Kyushu meteoritic Strecker analysis)"}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "AMN-electrophile route: aminomalononitrile capture of lactaldehyde to threonine-family nitrile precursor", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous conditions; aldehyde electrophile capture followed by network-internal hydrolytic rearrangement to threonine-family aminonitrile precursor"}, "mechanism": "Aminomalononitrile acts as a multifunctional C-N synthon, adding to aldehydic electrophiles and channeling carbon and nitrogen into threonine/allothreonine precursor space through a route distinct from canonical one-carbonyl Strecker assembly.", "reasoning": "This reaction is intentionally separated from the canonical Strecker step to address the prior compression problem. Thanassi 1975 supports AMN plus aldehydes leading, after hydrolysis, to threonine/allothreonine, but the detailed intermediate structure is less explicitly resolved than for the lactaldehyde Strecker branch. Therefore this node is represented as converging on the experimentally relevant threonine-family aminonitrile space while acknowledging partial mechanistic compression. This is literature-supported but less specific than rxn_008. (Thanassi, 1975)"}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine and allothreonine", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "prolonged aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools or during wet-dry/geothermal cycling; expected to yield diastereomeric threonine and allothreonine"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide/carboxyl equivalents to the alpha-amino acid products, preserving the expected threonine/allothreonine diastereomeric outcome.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to alpha-amino acids is the standard terminal step of Strecker-type synthesis and is explicitly framed in meteoritic Strecker discussions. The report also emphasizes that abiotic syntheses typically generate threonine together with allothreonine. (Kyushu meteoritic Strecker analysis; Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Ring et al., 1972)"}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Direct spark-discharge production of threonine and allothreonine", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_004", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "high-energy discharge, local plume heating", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide mineral deposition surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "reducing or locally reducing discharge system; product residues accumulate and wash into surface waters; threonine present at low abundance relative to glycine and largely racemic"}, "mechanism": "Complex atmospheric radical chemistry followed by aqueous post-processing yields a suite of amino acids directly, including threonine and allothreonine.", "reasoning": "Both Parker et al. 2011 and Ring et al. 1972 report threonine in spark-discharge residues, with Ring et al. explicitly confirming both threonine and allothreonine. This direct route is included as an experimentally grounded alternative path to the target, while also returning HCN and aldehyde feedstocks to the connected network. Mineral agents are again interpreted as environmental deposition/concentration surfaces to satisfy the schema. (Parker et al., 2011; Ring et al., 1972)"}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrothermal redox-buffered Strecker-style support and hydrolysis route to threonine from imported lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite", "magnetite", "mackinawite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "423K", "pressure": "10 bar", "catalyst": "pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite style redox buffer represented here by pyrite, magnetite, and FeS/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "hydrothermal Strecker-type conditions modeled on HCN/aldehyde/NH4+ experiments; included as a constrained route because threonine itself was not explicitly reported and hydroxy amino acids may degrade"}, "mechanism": "If lactaldehyde is delivered into hydrothermal flank settings, redox-buffered Strecker aminonitrile formation and partial hydrolysis can occur, but product persistence is limited by hydrothermal degradation of hydroxy amino acids.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is experimentally documented for several amino acids under 150 C and 10 bar with pyrite-pyrrhotite-magnetite buffers, but threonine was not explicitly tabulated; therefore this route is included only as a literature-constrained extension requiring imported lactaldehyde and explicitly acknowledging instability/degradation of hydroxy amino acids. It should be regarded as plausible but less directly demonstrated than the surface lactaldehyde route. (Andersson & Holm, 2000 summarizing Hennet et al., 1992; Bada et al., 1978; Keefe et al., 1995)"}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical cyanosulfidic threonine pathway from atmospheric cyanide", "description": "Spark-discharge feedstocks supply cyanide and acetaldehyde; acetaldehyde cyanohydrin is photoreduced to lactaldehyde, then Strecker assembly gives threonine aminonitrile and hydrolysis gives threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Glycolonitrile-first photoredox pathway", "description": "Atmospheric cyanide is converted to glycolonitrile, photoreduced to glycolaldehyde plus acetaldehyde, then passes through cyanohydrin and lactaldehyde to threonine aminonitrile and threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Direct spark-discharge threonine synthesis", "description": "High-energy atmospheric discharge directly generates threonine and allothreonine in complex amino-acid mixtures.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "AMN alternative route from atmospheric cyanide to threonine", "description": "Atmospheric cyanide oligomerizes to aminomalononitrile; independently generated lactaldehyde is captured by AMN-derived chemistry and hydrolyzed to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_007", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hybrid discharge-photoredox route via direct acetaldehyde supply", "description": "Acetaldehyde from discharge chemistry enters the cyanohydrin-photoreduction sequence without requiring the glycolonitrile branch.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hybrid discharge-photoredox route with HCN conditioning through formamide", "description": "HCN is held in surface reservoirs as formamide-linked cyanide chemistry before entering glycolonitrile photoredox chemistry and then the lactaldehyde Strecker module.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "HCN oligomer route merged with canonical lactaldehyde module", "description": "An HCN-rich pool simultaneously supports AMN formation and the canonical lactaldehyde Strecker route, yielding threonine through an alternative C-N assembly entry point.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal completion from surface-generated lactaldehyde", "description": "Surface photochemistry generates lactaldehyde, which is transported into hydrothermal flank settings where redox-buffered Strecker chemistry and hydrolysis can produce threonine, though with degradation risk.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Glycolonitrile-to-hydrothermal hybrid pathway", "description": "The full surface glycolonitrile photoredox sequence generates lactaldehyde, which then feeds a hydrothermal redox-buffered Strecker/hydrolysis step.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Surface network with parallel direct and indirect threonine production", "description": "A single plume-fed environment can yield some threonine directly by discharge while also building a larger threonine pool indirectly through the lactaldehyde aminonitrile route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_004", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_004", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_001", "rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn