{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T13:59:16.744124", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Threonine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] https://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\nhttps://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\n[4] [5] [9] [11] [15] [17] [18] [24] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\n[7] [12] REACTIONS OF AMINOMALONONITRILE WITH ... - HERO\nhttps://hero.epa.gov/reference/10713764/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n[10] [19] [23] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\n[13] [14] [16] https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\nhttps://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\n[20] [21] https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\nhttps://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\n[22] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.87\n- Feedback: This is a good to very good synthesis network overall. Its main strength is that it correctly centers threonine synthesis on the literature-supported lactaldehyde -> threonine aminonitrile -> threonine module, and it builds sensible convergent upstream routes through glycolonitrile, acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, HCN, and NH3. The strongest parts are the UV cyanosulfidic surface reactions, which align closely with Ritson and Sutherland and later systems-level treatments, and the final Strecker/hydrolysis logic is sound. The network also appropriately reflects the literature caveat that abiotic synthesis should give threonine together with allothreonine and that hydroxy amino acids are vulnerable to degradation under hydrothermal heating. Topologically, the network is connected, has adequate size, and contains several real hubs and convergence points. The main weaknesses are in the hydrothermal feedstock steps: direct CO2 -> formaldehyde is under-supported in the provided threonine-specific literature, and the ferrocyanide conditioning step is more conceptually right than chemically complete as written. The AMN branch is a legitimate alternative but is compressed too aggressively into the same aminonitrile node used for the canonical Strecker pathway. Mineral-agent compliance is mixed: surface photoredox chemistry implicitly needs CuCN/phosphate and sulfide sources, while the summary as provided does not clearly document all required mineral agents for every non-biochemical reaction. Despite these issues, the network meets target achievement and literature alignment well enough to be considered approved.\n- Issues: ['The AMN route is literature-supported in general, since aminomalononitrile can react with aldehydes and after hydrolysis yield threonine/allothreonine. However, the specific representation here is weaker than the Strecker branch because rxn_010 collapses a more complex AMN-electrophile chemistry into a single poorly specified step and labels the product as the same threonine aminonitrile node, which is probably an oversimplification. This pathway is plausible but less rigorous.', 'This convergent AMN-plus-lactaldehyde pathway has good conceptual design because it merges two literature-supported branches. Yet the decisive C-N bond-forming step remains too underspecified. The network correctly identifies AMN as an alternative threonine precursor route, but the mapping onto the same aminonitrile intermediate used in the Strecker sequence reduces mechanistic clarity.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: Overall, this is a good and mostly literature-aligned threonine synthesis network. Its strongest feature is the correct identification of lactaldehyde and threonine aminonitrile as central hubs, matching the deep research findings. The network also appropriately includes direct spark-discharge production, cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of lactaldehyde from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, and an AMN-based alternative route. Topologically, it is well connected, has multiple convergent routes, and achieves the target repeatedly. The biggest weaknesses are structural and compliance-related: the network claims a hydrothermal component but provides no mineral agents for the hydrothermal or surface reactions despite the required schema, and several surface steps are underspecified relative to the literature, especially the HCN to formamide to glycolonitrile segment. The hydrothermal route to threonine is weakly supported by the supplied literature and should be treated as speculative due to poor direct evidence for threonine formation and likely degradation of hydroxy amino acids at elevated temperature. Literature alignment is otherwise strong in concept, but because reaction-level citations and exact conditions are absent from the presented network, it falls short of full compliance with the requested synthesis-network standard.\n- Issues: ['This pathway captures the intended cyanosulfidic upstream logic, but the HCN to formamide to glycolonitrile sequence is weakly specified and not a well-supported direct route in the cited threonine literature. The downstream glycolonitrile photoreduction and lactaldehyde module are plausible, but the conditioning segment reduces confidence.', 'As with P2, the weakness is not in the lactaldehyde-to-threonine module but in the formamide-conditioned HCN route to glycolonitrile. The later steps are solid; the front-end chemistry is insufficiently supported in the supplied literature.', 'The network correctly treats hydrothermal chemistry as a support/completion route rather than the primary origin of threonine, but rxn_012 overstates hydrothermal confidence. Literature supports hydrothermal Strecker chemistry for some amino acids under mineral-buffered conditions, yet threonine specifically is not established and hydroxy amino acid instability at elevated temperature is a serious concern.', 'This hybrid suffers from both major weak points in the network: the under-supported formamide-to-glycolonitrile segment and the overstated hydrothermal completion step. Although connected, it is among the least convincing routes chemically.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network centers threonine synthesis on the literature-supported lactaldehyde -> threonine aminonitrile -> threonine module, while embedding that module in a connected prebiotic network spanning hydrothermal feedstock conditioning, surface cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry, atmospheric discharge production, and biochemical hydrolysis/selection. The dominant routes use UV-driven CuCN/H2S photoreduction to generate lactaldehyde from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, followed by Strecker conversion with NH3 and HCN to the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile and hydrolysis to threonine. Parallel convergence is provided by direct spark-discharge production of threonine, direct discharge production of lactaldehyde/HCN-class precursors that rain out into surface pools, and an alternative aminomalononitrile (AMN) electrophile route that yields threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis. Hydrothermal chemistry is treated conservatively as feedstock generation, redox buffering, cyanide conditioning, and limited Strecker support rather than as a primary direct CO2 -> threonine route, in accordance with the literature constraints and hydroxy-amino-acid instability at elevated temperature.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid/formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H5NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-3(5)2-4/h3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-diaminoprop-2-enedinitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminomalononitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"allothreonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent-like, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 on iron-sulfur phases to C1 reduced carbon.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included as conservative hydrothermal feedstock generation consistent with iron-sulfur vent chemistry and the instructions' required hydrothermal CO2 reduction module; it provides reduced carbon conditioning without asserting direct threonine formation. This is supportive context rather than a threonine-specific proven step, because the supplied threonine literature emphasizes Strecker and cyanosulfidic routes instead of direct CO2-to-threonine synthesis, and FeS/H2S direct amino-acid claims are specifically challenged (Andersson & Holm, 2000; Keefe et al., 1995).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic spark-discharge generation of HCN and NH3-bearing feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral collection/concentration after atmospheric discharge\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"products formed in reducing volcanic plume/discharge chemistry and rained into surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Atmospheric/plume discharge produces reactive C-N species that are captured and concentrated in surface waters on mineral shores.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Spark-discharge experiments and volcanic-plume interpretation support abiotic generation of HCN-class and NH3-bearing feedstocks that can wash into pools; Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning, reduced gases, and rainout accumulation in tidal settings, while Ring et al. showed discharge products include threonine/allothreonine in complex mixtures. Mineral agents here represent the required surface concentration/adsorption setting rather than the electrical discharge source itself (Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydration to formamide in UV-exposed surface pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/phosphate mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed shallow pool, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydration and photochemical conditioning of cyanide in surface aqueous environments yields formamide as a reactive C-N reservoir.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is included only as a connected C-N reservoir node, not as a mandatory front-end to the main threonine route. The threonine literature notes UV chemistry from HCN and water to formamide/nucleobases in broader prebiotic contexts, but the core threonine network does not require this step; therefore this reaction is a cautious connector rather than a central claim, avoiding the overextended formamide-to-glycolonitrile logic criticized previously (general prebiotic UV chemistry contextualized alongside Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanide chemistry to glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surface concentration under UV-accessible conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide-rich pool; feedstock accumulation from atmospheric/plume delivery\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide-derived C1/C2 chemistry in pooled surface settings produces glycolonitrile as a key nitrile node for photoredox reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland use glycolonitrile as the experimentally defined starting substrate for first-stage photoreduction to glycolaldehyde. The supplied report identifies glycolonitrile as a key upstream node in the cyanosulfidic network, so it is included directly as a literature-grounded precursor rather than derived through a speculative multistep sequence (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoredox reduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (Cu-sulfide source for CuCN generation)\", \"phosphate minerals (33 mM sodium phosphate equivalent)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"solid CuCN generated from copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H2S, 33 mM phosphate, 10 mol % CuCN, 254 nm UV, quartz vessel, 2 h\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CuCN/H2S photoredox chemistry generates reducing equivalents that convert glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde, with acetaldehyde among aldehydic coproducts.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This directly follows the quantitatively specified Ritson-Sutherland system: 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H2S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, 10 mol % CuCN, 254 nm irradiation, giving glycolaldehyde in 42% yield after 2 h and acetaldehyde among accompanying aldehydes. The mineral wording reflects the paper's geochemical bridge in which copper sulfide dissolution in cyanide solution provides CuCN and FeS dissolution can supply sulfide reductant (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from acetaldehyde and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-surface concentration in cyanide-rich pool\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, ammonia availability controls partitioning between cyanohydrin and aminonitrile branches\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic cyanide addition to acetaldehyde forms the cyanohydrin precursor required for second-stage photoreduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied report identifies acetaldehyde cyanohydrin as the dedicated precursor node leading by photoreduction to lactaldehyde. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussion also emphasizes cyanohydrin versus aminonitrile branching as a function of ammonia availability, making this a mechanistically central node rather than a speculative compression (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Kyushu meteoritic analysis, associated report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoredox reduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (Cu-sulfide source for CuCN generation)\", \"phosphate minerals (33 mM sodium phosphate equivalent)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"solid CuCN generated from copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"H2S present, 254 nm UV, 2 h irradiation; lactaldehyde obtained in 19% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Second-stage CuCN/H2S photoreduction of the cyanohydrin yields the aldehyde-level Strecker precursor lactaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the most specific upstream threonine step in the literature: Ritson & Sutherland report that irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield after 2 h, and they explicitly identify lactaldehyde as the Strecker precursor of (allo-)threonine. Green et al. later restated this lactaldehyde-generating node within the broader hydrated-electron cyanosulfidic network (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN formation by HCN oligomerization\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentration/polymerization on mineral substrates\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN-rich evaporative pool, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomerization yields aminomalononitrile as a multifunctional C/N synthon.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"AMN is a literature-supported alternative branch point for amino-acid formation, though its accumulation and diversion into refractory HCN polymers remain open questions. It is included explicitly because Thanassi used aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry to access threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis, but this branch is treated as secondary to the lactaldehyde-Strecker route (Thanassi, 1975; Green et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Lactaldehyde Strecker conversion to threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-aided concentration in aqueous pool\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"days to weeks holding time; proceeds via cyanohydrin/iminium-Strecker sequence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form imine/iminium species, followed by cyanide addition to produce the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The core threonine-forming module is directly supported: Ritson & Sutherland report that when HCN and NH3 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was smoothly converted via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile; the report notes timescales of days to weeks. The meteoritic Strecker framework likewise identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021; Kyushu meteoritic analysis).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN plus lactaldehyde electrophile chemistry to threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"mild to moderate\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous reaction with subsequent hydrolysis; exact environmental residence time variable\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"AMN acts as a multifunctional C-N synthon that reacts with aldehydes such as lactaldehyde, and subsequent hydrolysis yields hydroxy amino acids including threonine and allothreonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is intentionally represented as a distinct AMN-electrophile-plus-hydrolysis branch rather than being collapsed into the canonical Strecker aminonitrile node, addressing the prior criticism. Thanassi specifically reported that AMN reacted with electrophiles including aldehydes and, after hydrolysis, yielded amino acids including threonine and allothreonine. Because the exact intermediate identities are not resolved in the provided report, the step is kept as the experimentally supported net transformation and explicitly acknowledged as mechanistically less resolved than the lactaldehyde Strecker route (Thanassi, 1975).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine and allothreonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null, null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable, mild aqueous to geothermal cycling\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic aqueous hydrolysis in pools or compartments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis converts the Strecker intermediate into the corresponding alpha-amino acids, yielding diastereomeric threonine/allothreonine mixtures.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the standard final step of Strecker chemistry, and the meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussion explicitly frames aminonitrile hydrolysis as producing alpha-amino acids. Because the lactaldehyde precursor yields an (allo-)threonine aminonitrile, the expected outcome is a threonine/allothreonine mixture, consistent with classic abiotic observations of both diastereomers (Kyushu meteoritic analysis; Ring et al., 1972).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct spark-discharge formation of threonine and allothreonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"post-discharge mineral concentration in aqueous tidal or plume fallout settings\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"products derive from reducing gas discharge residues; racemic/chiral mixtures expected\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex discharge chemistry generates reactive C-N intermediates that, after rainout and aqueous processing, furnish amino-acid mixtures including threonine and allothreonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This net surface route captures the empirical observation that spark-discharge systems produce threonine directly in complex mixtures: Parker et al. reanalyzed the 1958 H2S-rich Miller residues and identified threonine among many amino acids, while Ring et al. directly confirmed both threonine and allothreonine in methane-nitrogen-water discharge products with traces of ammonia. Because the supplied literature does not resolve every intermediate in the discharge branch, the reaction is represented as an experimentally supported net production route rather than a detailed mechanistic sequence (Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic photoredox-Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN-derived glycolonitrile is photoreduced to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde, converted to acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, photoreduced to lactaldehyde, then subjected to Strecker chemistry and hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoredox route with direct HCN pool delivery\",\n      \"description\": \"Atmospheric/discharge generation of HCN and NH3 feeds directly into the surface photoredox module leading to lactaldehyde and then to threonine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolonitrile-to-lactaldehyde branch emphasizing acetaldehyde coproduct\",\n      \"description\": \"The Ritson-Sutherland first-stage reduction generates acetaldehyde as a coproduct, which is trapped as its cyanohydrin and reduced to lactaldehyde before Strecker completion.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Lactaldehyde-centered Strecker completion\",\n      \"description\": \"Once lactaldehyde is available in surface pools, addition of HCN and NH3 gives the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile and hydrolysis yields threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"AMN alternative using lactaldehyde electrophile chemistry\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN oligomerization produces aminomalononitrile, which reacts with lactaldehyde and after hydrolysis yields threonine and allothreonine without passing through the canonical Strecker aminonitrile node.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct discharge production pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Spark-discharge chemistry in reducing volcanic-plume analogues yields threonine/allothreonine directly in product mixtures that are collected in surface waters.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface supported photoredox route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduction supplies reduced carbon context and vent-derived feedstocks that connect into cyanide-rich surface pools where the cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde route operates.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-supported AMN route\",\n      \"description\": \"Reduced hydrothermal feedstock generation supports cyanide accumulation at the surface, where HCN oligomerization to AMN converges with lactaldehyde produced by photoredox chemistry to yield threonine after hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface C-N reservoir assisted route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN in UV-exposed pools is partially conditioned into formamide while the main cyanide inventory proceeds through glycolonitrile and the canonical lactaldehyde Strecker route, reflecting mixed surface C-N chemistry without making formamide obligatory.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Rainout and compartmentalized holding-time route\",\n      \"description\": \"Discharge-generated cyanide and ammonia rain into mineral pools, the CuCN/H2S photoredox sequence produces lactaldehyde, and prolonged pool residence over days to weeks allows Strecker aminonitrile accumulation followed by hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "The network centers threonine synthesis on the literature-supported lactaldehyde -> threonine aminonitrile -> threonine module, while embedding that module in a connected prebiotic network spanning hydrothermal feedstock conditioning, surface cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry, atmospheric discharge production, and biochemical hydrolysis/selection. The dominant routes use UV-driven CuCN/H2S photoreduction to generate lactaldehyde from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, followed by Strecker conversion with NH3 and HCN to the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile and hydrolysis to threonine. Parallel convergence is provided by direct spark-discharge production of threonine, direct discharge production of lactaldehyde/HCN-class precursors that rain out into surface pools, and an alternative aminomalononitrile (AMN) electrophile route that yields threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis. Hydrothermal chemistry is treated conservatively as feedstock generation, redox buffering, cyanide conditioning, and limited Strecker support rather than as a primary direct CO2 -> threonine route, in accordance with the literature constraints and hydroxy-amino-acid instability at elevated temperature.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "acetaldehyde cyanohydrin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-3(5)2-4/h3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H4N2", "iupac_name": "2,3-diaminoprop-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "aminomalononitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "allothreonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent-like, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 on iron-sulfur phases to C1 reduced carbon.", "reasoning": "Included as conservative hydrothermal feedstock generation consistent with iron-sulfur vent chemistry and the instructions' required hydrothermal CO2 reduction module; it provides reduced carbon conditioning without asserting direct threonine formation. This is supportive context rather than a threonine-specific proven step, because the supplied threonine literature emphasizes Strecker and cyanosulfidic routes instead of direct CO2-to-threonine synthesis, and FeS/H2S direct amino-acid claims are specifically challenged (Andersson & Holm, 2000; Keefe et al., 1995)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Volcanic spark-discharge generation of HCN and NH3-bearing feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral collection/concentration after atmospheric discharge", "aqueous": "true", "other": "products formed in reducing volcanic plume/discharge chemistry and rained into surface pools"}, "mechanism": "Atmospheric/plume discharge produces reactive C-N species that are captured and concentrated in surface waters on mineral shores.", "reasoning": "Spark-discharge experiments and volcanic-plume interpretation support abiotic generation of HCN-class and NH3-bearing feedstocks that can wash into pools; Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning, reduced gases, and rainout accumulation in tidal settings, while Ring et al. showed discharge products include threonine/allothreonine in complex mixtures. Mineral agents here represent the required surface concentration/adsorption setting rather than the electrical discharge source itself (Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "HCN hydration to formamide in UV-exposed surface pools", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/phosphate mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow pool, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Hydration and photochemical conditioning of cyanide in surface aqueous environments yields formamide as a reactive C-N reservoir.", "reasoning": "Formamide is included only as a connected C-N reservoir node, not as a mandatory front-end to the main threonine route. The threonine literature notes UV chemistry from HCN and water to formamide/nucleobases in broader prebiotic contexts, but the core threonine network does not require this step; therefore this reaction is a cautious connector rather than a central claim, avoiding the overextended formamide-to-glycolonitrile logic criticized previously (general prebiotic UV chemistry contextualized alongside Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface cyanide chemistry to glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surface concentration under UV-accessible conditions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanide-rich pool; feedstock accumulation from atmospheric/plume delivery"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide-derived C1/C2 chemistry in pooled surface settings produces glycolonitrile as a key nitrile node for photoredox reduction.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland use glycolonitrile as the experimentally defined starting substrate for first-stage photoreduction to glycolaldehyde. The supplied report identifies glycolonitrile as a key upstream node in the cyanosulfidic network, so it is included directly as a literature-grounded precursor rather than derived through a speculative multistep sequence (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "UV photoredox reduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (Cu-sulfide source for CuCN generation)", "phosphate minerals (33 mM sodium phosphate equivalent)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "solid CuCN generated from copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution", "aqueous": "true", "other": "10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H2S, 33 mM phosphate, 10 mol % CuCN, 254 nm UV, quartz vessel, 2 h"}, "mechanism": "CuCN/H2S photoredox chemistry generates reducing equivalents that convert glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde, with acetaldehyde among aldehydic coproducts.", "reasoning": "This directly follows the quantitatively specified Ritson-Sutherland system: 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H2S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, 10 mol % CuCN, 254 nm irradiation, giving glycolaldehyde in 42% yield after 2 h and acetaldehyde among accompanying aldehydes. The mineral wording reflects the paper's geochemical bridge in which copper sulfide dissolution in cyanide solution provides CuCN and FeS dissolution can supply sulfide reductant (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation from acetaldehyde and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-surface concentration in cyanide-rich pool", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, ammonia availability controls partitioning between cyanohydrin and aminonitrile branches"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic cyanide addition to acetaldehyde forms the cyanohydrin precursor required for second-stage photoreduction.", "reasoning": "The supplied report identifies acetaldehyde cyanohydrin as the dedicated precursor node leading by photoreduction to lactaldehyde. The meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussion also emphasizes cyanohydrin versus aminonitrile branching as a function of ammonia availability, making this a mechanistically central node rather than a speculative compression (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Kyushu meteoritic analysis, associated report)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV photoredox reduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (Cu-sulfide source for CuCN generation)", "phosphate minerals (33 mM sodium phosphate equivalent)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "solid CuCN generated from copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution", "aqueous": "true", "other": "H2S present, 254 nm UV, 2 h irradiation; lactaldehyde obtained in 19% yield"}, "mechanism": "Second-stage CuCN/H2S photoreduction of the cyanohydrin yields the aldehyde-level Strecker precursor lactaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the most specific upstream threonine step in the literature: Ritson & Sutherland report that irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield after 2 h, and they explicitly identify lactaldehyde as the Strecker precursor of (allo-)threonine. Green et al. later restated this lactaldehyde-generating node within the broader hydrated-electron cyanosulfidic network (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "AMN formation by HCN oligomerization", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface concentration/polymerization on mineral substrates", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN-rich evaporative pool, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "HCN oligomerization yields aminomalononitrile as a multifunctional C/N synthon.", "reasoning": "AMN is a literature-supported alternative branch point for amino-acid formation, though its accumulation and diversion into refractory HCN polymers remain open questions. It is included explicitly because Thanassi used aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry to access threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis, but this branch is treated as secondary to the lactaldehyde-Strecker route (Thanassi, 1975; Green et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Lactaldehyde Strecker conversion to threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-aided concentration in aqueous pool", "aqueous": "true", "other": "days to weeks holding time; proceeds via cyanohydrin/iminium-Strecker sequence"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form imine/iminium species, followed by cyanide addition to produce the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "The core threonine-forming module is directly supported: Ritson & Sutherland report that when HCN and NH3 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was smoothly converted via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile; the report notes timescales of days to weeks. The meteoritic Strecker framework likewise identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021; Kyushu meteoritic analysis)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "AMN plus lactaldehyde electrophile chemistry to threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "mild to moderate", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous reaction with subsequent hydrolysis; exact environmental residence time variable"}, "mechanism": "AMN acts as a multifunctional C-N synthon that reacts with aldehydes such as lactaldehyde, and subsequent hydrolysis yields hydroxy amino acids including threonine and allothreonine.", "reasoning": "This reaction is intentionally represented as a distinct AMN-electrophile-plus-hydrolysis branch rather than being collapsed into the canonical Strecker aminonitrile node, addressing the prior criticism. Thanassi specifically reported that AMN reacted with electrophiles including aldehydes and, after hydrolysis, yielded amino acids including threonine and allothreonine. Because the exact intermediate identities are not resolved in the provided report, the step is kept as the experimentally supported net transformation and explicitly acknowledged as mechanistically less resolved than the lactaldehyde Strecker route (Thanassi, 1975)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine and allothreonine", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable, mild aqueous to geothermal cycling", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic aqueous hydrolysis in pools or compartments"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis converts the Strecker intermediate into the corresponding alpha-amino acids, yielding diastereomeric threonine/allothreonine mixtures.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the standard final step of Strecker chemistry, and the meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussion explicitly frames aminonitrile hydrolysis as producing alpha-amino acids. Because the lactaldehyde precursor yields an (allo-)threonine aminonitrile, the expected outcome is a threonine/allothreonine mixture, consistent with classic abiotic observations of both diastereomers (Kyushu meteoritic analysis; Ring et al., 1972)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Direct spark-discharge formation of threonine and allothreonine", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "post-discharge mineral concentration in aqueous tidal or plume fallout settings", "aqueous": "true", "other": "products derive from reducing gas discharge residues; racemic/chiral mixtures expected"}, "mechanism": "Complex discharge chemistry generates reactive C-N intermediates that, after rainout and aqueous processing, furnish amino-acid mixtures including threonine and allothreonine.", "reasoning": "This net surface route captures the empirical observation that spark-discharge systems produce threonine directly in complex mixtures: Parker et al. reanalyzed the 1958 H2S-rich Miller residues and identified threonine among many amino acids, while Ring et al. directly confirmed both threonine and allothreonine in methane-nitrogen-water discharge products with traces of ammonia. Because the supplied literature does not resolve every intermediate in the discharge branch, the reaction is represented as an experimentally supported net production route rather than a detailed mechanistic sequence (Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical cyanosulfidic photoredox-Strecker route", "description": "HCN-derived glycolonitrile is photoreduced to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde, converted to acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, photoreduced to lactaldehyde, then subjected to Strecker chemistry and hydrolysis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Photoredox route with direct HCN pool delivery", "description": "Atmospheric/discharge generation of HCN and NH3 feeds directly into the surface photoredox module leading to lactaldehyde and then to threonine aminonitrile.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Glycolonitrile-to-lactaldehyde branch emphasizing acetaldehyde coproduct", "description": "The Ritson-Sutherland first-stage reduction generates acetaldehyde as a coproduct, which is trapped as its cyanohydrin and reduced to lactaldehyde before Strecker completion.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Lactaldehyde-centered Strecker completion", "description": "Once lactaldehyde is available in surface pools, addition of HCN and NH3 gives the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile and hydrolysis yields threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "AMN alternative using lactaldehyde electrophile chemistry", "description": "HCN oligomerization produces aminomalononitrile, which reacts with lactaldehyde and after hydrolysis yields threonine and allothreonine without passing through the canonical Strecker aminonitrile node.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_008", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Direct discharge production pathway", "description": "Spark-discharge chemistry in reducing volcanic-plume analogues yields threonine/allothreonine directly in product mixtures that are collected in surface waters.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface supported photoredox route", "description": "Hydrothermal reduction supplies reduced carbon context and vent-derived feedstocks that connect into cyanide-rich surface pools where the cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde route operates.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal-supported AMN route", "description": "Reduced hydrothermal feedstock generation supports cyanide accumulation at the surface, where HCN oligomerization to AMN converges with lactaldehyde produced by photoredox chemistry to yield threonine after hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_008", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_012", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Surface C-N reservoir assisted route", "description": "HCN in UV-exposed pools is partially conditioned into formamide while the main cyanide inventory proceeds through glycolonitrile and the canonical lactaldehyde Strecker route, reflecting mixed surface C-N chemistry without making formamide obligatory.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Rainout and compartmentalized holding-time route", "description": "Discharge-generated cyanide and ammonia rain into mineral pools, the CuCN/H2S photoredox sequence produces lactaldehyde, and prolonged pool residence over days to weeks allows Strecker aminonitrile accumulation followed by hydrolysis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_013"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_004", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": []}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 112901.59702301025, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T14:01:09.650018", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: The network centers threonine synthesis on the literature-supported lactaldehyde -> threonine aminonitrile -> threonine module, while embedding that module in a connected prebiotic network spanning hydrothermal feedstock conditioning, surface cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry, atmospheric discharge production, and biochemical hydrolysis/selection. The dominant routes use UV-driven CuCN/H2S photoreduction to generate lactaldehyde from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, followed by Strecker conversion with NH3 and HCN to the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile and hydrolysis to threonine. Parallel convergence is provided by direct spark-discharge production of threonine, direct discharge production of lactaldehyde/HCN-class precursors that rain out into surface pools, and an alternative aminomalononitrile (AMN) electrophile route that yields threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis. Hydrothermal chemistry is treated conservatively as feedstock generation, redox buffering, cyanide conditioning, and limited Strecker support rather than as a primary direct CO2 -> threonine route, in accordance with the literature constraints and hydroxy-amino-acid instability at elevated temperature.\n\nMOLECULES (15 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: CH2O2 (formic acid/formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_004: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: NH3 (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: CH3NO (formamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C2H3NO (glycolonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C3H5NO (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C3H6O2 (lactaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C3H4N2 (aminomalononitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C4H8N2O (threonine aminonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H9NO3 (threonine) [target]\n  - mol_015: C4H9NO3 (allothreonine) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (12 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_003 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001 -> mol_004, mol_005 (Volcanic spark-discharge generation of HCN and NH3-bearing feedstocks) [Surface]\n  - rxn_003: mol_004 -> mol_006 (HCN hydration to formamide in UV-exposed surface pools) [Surface]\n  - rxn_004: mol_004 -> mol_007 (Surface cyanide chemistry to glycolonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_007 -> mol_008, mol_009 (UV photoredox reduction of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_009, mol_004 -> mol_010 (Cyanohydrin formation from acetaldehyde and HCN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_010 -> mol_011 (UV photoredox reduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_004 -> mol_012 (AMN formation by HCN oligomerization) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_011, mol_004, mol_005 -> mol_013 (Lactaldehyde Strecker conversion to threonine aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_012, mol_011 -> mol_014, mol_015 (AMN plus lactaldehyde electrophile chemistry to threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_011: mol_013 -> mol_014, mol_015 (Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine and allothreonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_012: mol_004, mol_005 -> mol_014, mol_015 (Direct spark-discharge formation of threonine and allothreonine) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Canonical cyanosulfidic photoredox-Strecker route (7 steps)\n  - P2: Photoredox route with direct HCN pool delivery (7 steps)\n  - P3: Glycolonitrile-to-lactaldehyde branch emphasizing acetaldehyde coproduct (6 steps)\n  - P4: Lactaldehyde-centered Strecker completion (2 steps)\n  - P5: AMN alternative using lactaldehyde electrophile chemistry (7 steps)\n  - P6: Direct discharge production pathway (2 steps)\n  - P7: Hydrothermal-to-surface supported photoredox route (8 steps)\n  - P8: Hydrothermal-supported AMN route (8 steps)\n  - P9: Surface C-N reservoir assisted route (8 steps)\n  - P10: Rainout and compartmentalized holding-time route (7 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_004, mol_007, mol_009, mol_011, mol_013\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 3\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\nMolecule-specific constraints that shape plausible prebiotic routes\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid whose prebiotic formation is complicated by (i) the need to install both an amino group and a hydroxyl-bearing sidechain and (ii) the fact that two diastereomeric products are typically expected: threonine and allothreonine. The co-occurrence of threonine and allothreonine in abiotic product mixtures is explicitly reported in classic spark-discharge experiments, where both \u201cthreonine\u201d and \u201callothreonine\u201d were confirmed among the synthesized amino acids. [1]\nA key practical implication for network design is that many plausible routes do not make threonine \u201cdirectly\u201d from CO\u2082; instead, they converge on a specific aldehyde-level carbonyl precursor\u2014lactaldehyde (2\u2011hydroxypropanal)\u2014followed by Strecker-type conversion to an aminonitrile and then hydrolysis to the amino acid. This lactaldehyde-centered view is articulated both in cyanosulfidic photoredox work (where lactaldehyde is produced photochemically from nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) and in meteoritic Strecker-cyanohydrin discussions (where lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the carbonyl precursor for threonine/allothreonine). [2]\nHydrothermal persistence is also a constraint: hydroxy amino acids (including serine and threonine) can undergo dehydration and other degradation pathways during diagenesis/hydrothermal exposure, which matters when evaluating vent-based syntheses or post-synthesis survival. [3]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes for threonine\nElectric-discharge (atmospheric / volcanic-plume) synthesis.\nA strong line of experimental evidence for abiotic threonine production comes from spark-discharge experiments designed to simulate reducing (or locally reducing) atmospheres. In the 1958 H\u2082S-rich Miller experiment reanalysis, E. T. Parker[4] and coauthors (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences) report that residues produced from a spark discharge acting on a gas mixture containing H\u2082S, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and CO\u2082 contained a broad suite of amino acids and amines, including threonine; chiral amino acids were largely racemic within measurement uncertainty, supporting an abiotic origin (rather than modern biological contamination). [5]\nEarlier work also directly confirmed threonine and allothreonine in discharge products from mixtures including methane, nitrogen, water, and traces of ammonia. [1]\nUV-driven cyanosulfidic photoredox + Strecker assembly via lactaldehyde.\nA second, mechanistically explicit route emerges from cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry associated with Daniel J. Ritson[6] and John D. Sutherland[7] (2013, Angewandte Chemie International Edition). In this system, UV (254 nm) photoredox chemistry reduces nitriles/cyanohydrins to generate aldehydes (including lactaldehyde, the threonine carbonyl precursor), and subsequent addition of HCN and NH\u2083 yields the corresponding Strecker aminonitriles (including the (allo-)threonine aminonitrile). [8]\nA later synthesis-and-systems perspective by Nicholas J. Green[9], Xu, and Sutherland (2021, Journal of the American Chemical Society) explicitly situates this \u201clactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\u201d step inside a broader UV-photochemical network driven by hydrated-electron photochemistry and cyanosulfidic redox cycling. [10]\nHCN-oligomer / aminomalononitrile (AMN) chemistry as an alternative C\u2013N assembly route.\nA distinct, often-overlooked proposal is that HCN oligomers provide multifunctional C/N building blocks. In this vein, George Thanassi[11] (1975, Journal of Molecular Evolution) reports that reacting aminomalononitrile (a key HCN oligomer) with electrophiles (including aldehydes) followed by hydrolysis yields a range of amino acids, including threonine and allothreonine. This route is attractive for network design because it bypasses the need to pre-form lactaldehyde in bulk; the tradeoff is that selectivity, geochemical plausibility of AMN accumulation, and competing polymerization pathways remain active questions. [12]\nParent-body (meteoritic) Strecker\u2013cyanohydrin synthesis as evidence of a natural \u201cthreonine module.\u201d\nAlthough not an Earth experiment per se, carbonaceous-chondrite organic chemistry provides a natural laboratory for reactions relevant to early Earth delivery and corroborates mechanistic plausibility. A detailed treatment in a Kyushu University-hosted report (associated with threonine/hydroxy-amino-acid analyses in carbonaceous chondrites) describes Strecker-cyanohydrin synthesis where aldehydes/ketones + NH\u2083 \u2192 imines \u2192 CN\u207b addition \u2192 hydrolysis to \u03b1\u2011amino acids, and it explicitly identifies lactaldehyde as the carbonyl precursor for threonine and/or allo-threonine. [13]\nKey intermediates and precursors that define a threonine synthesis network\nAcross the most experimentally grounded routes, threonine sits at the end of a relatively consistent intermediate chain:\nThe minimal \u201cStrecker module\u201d requires a carbonyl compound, ammonia (or another nitrogen source that can generate an imine), and cyanide; the carbonyl required for threonine/allothreonine is lactaldehyde. [14]\nIn cyanosulfidic photoredox networks, the upstream pool can be generated from HCN-derived nitriles and cyanohydrins, with hydrogen sulfide acting as terminal reductant and Cu(I) cyanide functioning as a photoredox-active catalyst/surface. Key intermediates and branch points in the Ritson\u2013Sutherland sequence include: glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde (and formaldehyde, acetaldehyde as side/rearranged products), acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile-type node) \u2192 lactaldehyde, and then lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile in the presence of added HCN and NH\u2083. [8]\nIn spark-discharge contexts, the primary \u201cprecursor-generating\u201d chemistry is atmospheric/plume radical chemistry producing HCN, aldehydes/ketones, and related C\u2013N intermediates that can rain out and further react in surface waters\u2014an explicit motivation for the volcanic-plume framing of Miller-type experiments. [15]\nA key branching control is ammonia availability: the meteoritic discussion emphasizes that ammonia-rich environments favor aminonitrile (amino acid) pathways, whereas ammonia-poor settings favor cyanohydrins and hydroxy acids\u2014directly impacting whether the threonine branch is expressed efficiently. [13]\nReaction mechanisms, conditions, yields, and selectivity\nUV photoredox \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 (allo-)threonine aminonitrile\nThe most quantitatively specified prebiotic route to a threonine precursor is the UV photoredox chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013, Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.), which directly reports yields for lactaldehyde formation under defined conditions:\nA representative system for first-stage reduction used 10 mM glycolonitrile, 30 mM H\u2082S, 33 mM sodium phosphate, plus solid CuCN (10 mol % relative to glycolonitrile), irradiated at 254 nm in a quartz cuvette; after 2 h, glycolaldehyde (detected as hydrate) formed in 42% yield in solution, alongside other aldehydic products including acetaldehyde. [8]\nCritically, \u201csecond-stage\u201d cyanohydrin photoreductions in the same study yield the dedicated threonine carbonyl precursor: irradiation of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin furnished lactaldehyde in 19% yield (after 2 h irradiation). Lactaldehyde is explicitly identified as the Strecker precursor of \u201c(allo-)threonine.\u201d [8]\nDownstream assembly to the threonine aminonitrile is demonstrated by adding HCN and ammonia: when HCN and NH\u2083 were added to photoreduction products, lactaldehyde was \u201csmoothly converted\u201d via its cyanohydrin to the (allo-)threonine Strecker intermediate aminonitrile (aminonitrile 22 in the paper\u2019s numbering). Timescales reported for aminonitrile formation in these systems are days to weeks, indicating that geochemical \u201cholding times\u201d and compartmentalization could matter. [8]\nMechanistically, this route couples: (i) photoredox reduction of nitrile/cyanohydrin nodes to aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) and (ii) conventional Strecker-type conversion (aldehyde \u2192 imine \u2192 aminonitrile) once NH\u2083 and CN\u207b/HCN are available; hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the expected final step in Strecker frameworks, and the meteoritic Strecker discussion explicitly frames hydrolysis of aminonitriles as producing \u03b1-amino acids. [16]\nA systems-level restatement by Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, JACS) emphasizes that photoreduction of the relevant cyanohydrin node leads to lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde then yields a threonine precursor aminonitrile by addition of HCN and NH\u2083, embedding this step inside a broader cyanosulfidic network. [10]\nSpark discharge / volcanic plume simulation \u2192 threonine in complex amino-acid mixtures\nIn Parker et al. (2011, PNAS), reanalysis of archived Miller-type residues from a 1958 discharge experiment (gas mixture including CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, CO\u2082) identified 23 amino acids and 4 amines; the paper explicitly notes threonine among amino acids generated by this discharge chemistry and interprets racemic chiral amino acids (D/L \u2248 1 within stated uncertainty) as evidence against modern biological contamination. [17]\nQuantitatively, Parker et al. present product abundances as molar ratios relative to glycine (=1). In their Fig. 2, threonine appears at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 scale relative to glycine (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted point on a log molar-ratio axis). [18]\nIn an earlier and more expansive discharge study, Ring et al. (1972, PNAS) report that electric discharges in a methane\u2013nitrogen\u2013water system (with traces of ammonia) produced a wide set of amino acids, and explicitly confirm both threonine and allothreonine (alongside serine and others) by ion-exchange chromatography and GC\u2013MS. [1]\nThese discharge pathways are usually interpreted as producing amino acids via formation of reactive small C\u2013N intermediates (HCN, aldehydes/ketones) followed by aqueous-phase assembly (often Strecker-type), and Parker et al. explicitly connect volcanic lightning + reduced gases to generation of HCN and other intermediates that can wash out and accumulate in tidal settings. [15]\nHCN-oligomer (AMN) electrophile chemistry \u2192 threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis\nThanassi (1975, J. Mol. Evol.) provides experimental evidence that aminomalononitrile-derived chemistry can yield threonine and allothreonine after hydrolysis when AMN is reacted with electrophiles (including aldehydes) under mild conditions. The study explicitly states that amino acids (including threonine/allothreonine) were identified and quantified from hydrolysates. [12]\nFrom a mechanism standpoint, AMN functions as a multifunctional C\u2013N synthon, offering an alternative to \u201csingle-carbonyl + HCN + NH\u2083\u201d assembly; its prebiotic plausibility hinges on whether AMN can accumulate at useful concentrations without being diverted into intractable HCN polymers\u2014an issue treated as part of the broader \u201cHCN chemistry\u201d challenge space in origin-of-life literature. [19]\nHydrothermal Strecker-type synthesis: relevance and limitations for threonine specifically\nHydrothermal Strecker synthesis under mineral-buffered redox conditions is experimentally documented for several amino acids, demonstrating that Strecker chemistry can proceed in plausible vent/flank conditions if aldehydes/ketones and cyanide are available. Andersson & Holm (2000, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere) summarize hydrothermal experiments (Hennet et al., 1992) using HCN, CH\u2082O, and NH\u2084Cl at 150\u202f\u00b0C and 10 bar in the presence of a pyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite buffer; reported products include mM-level glycine (\u22489\u201312 mM) and lower but measurable levels of other amino acids (e.g., alanine \u22480.5\u20131.3 mM; aspartate and glutamate at \u22480.28\u20130.36 mM and \u22480.064\u20130.100 mM, respectively). [20]\nHowever, threonine itself is not among the explicitly tabulated products in that summary table, highlighting a practical bottleneck: even if hydrothermal Strecker chemistry is viable in general, demonstrating threonine specifically requires (i) access to lactaldehyde (or a direct hydrothermal pathway to lactaldehyde/lactaldehyde equivalents) and (ii) managing the competing high-temperature degradation chemistry that can disproportionately affect hydroxy amino acids. [21]\nA further caution for purely vent-centric \u201cCO\u2082 \u2192 amino acids\u201d narratives is that some claimed FeS/H\u2082S-driven syntheses have not held up; Keefe et al. (1995, PNAS) report that their FeS/H\u2082S system did not produce amino acids from CO\u2082 (nor via proposed reductive amination/carboxylation), sharpening the distinction between (a) Strecker-type routes requiring carbonyls + CN\u207b and (b) hypothesized direct CO\u2082 fixation-to-amino-acid routes. [22]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces implicated in threonine-relevant steps\nCu(I) cyanide (CuCN) as a photoredox-active heterogeneous catalyst/surface.\nIn the Ritson\u2013Sutherland photoredox system, CuCN is added as a solid; mixing generates a fine dark precipitate that is irradiated, consistent with heterogeneous photoredox cycling and surface-mediated electron production. [8]\nGreen et al. (2021, JACS) discuss Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanocuprate photoredox cycling as a route to hydrated electrons and connect this catalysis to the production of amino-acid Strecker precursors, including the threonine aminonitrile precursor derived from lactaldehyde. [10]\nSulfide minerals as sources of H\u2082S (reductant) and CuCN-generating Cu\u2013S chemistry.\nRitson & Sutherland explicitly note a plausible geochemical source: dissolution of copper sulfide minerals in cyanide solution could generate CuCN catalysts, and dissolution of FeS could provide additional H\u2082S reductant\u2014an explicit mineralogical bridge between rock chemistry and the photoredox network. [8]\nFerrocyanide as a cyanide concentrator and potential \u201cfeedstock conditioner.\u201d\nRitson & Sutherland also emphasize that cyanide can be concentrated by complexation with Fe\u00b2\u207a to form ferrocyanide, and that thermal processing of mixed ferrocyanide salts can yield mixtures containing cyanide, ammonia, and cyanamide upon rehydration\u2014reagents directly relevant to Strecker chemistry and linked nucleotide-precursor reactions. [8]\nPyrite\u2013pyrrhotite\u2013magnetite and silicate buffers in hydrothermal simulations.\nAndersson & Holm\u2019s redox-buffered hydrothermal framework highlights the use of pyrite (FeS\u2082), pyrrhotite (FeS), and magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) to constrain oxygen fugacity (redox), and K\u2011feldspar\u2013muscovite\u2013quartz assemblages to influence pH via ion activity control\u2014key when extrapolating laboratory hydrothermal yields to natural settings. [20]\nEnvironmental context and the main open challenges for threonine\nMost relevant environments by route.\nFor spark-discharge threonine formation, the empirical basis is strongest for localized, reducing volcanic-plume or eruption-lightning environments, where mixtures of reduced gases (e.g., CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) and oxidized components (e.g., CO\u2082) can coexist transiently; Parker et al. explicitly argue such localized plume chemistry could generate HCN and other intermediates that rain out and accumulate in tidal zones, supporting subsequent aqueous synthesis steps. [15]\nFor UV photoredox threonine-precursor formation, the most relevant setting is a sunlit surface environment that can sustain UV photochemistry (at least episodically) and maintain access to cyanide and sulfide redox pairs; Green et al. note that low H\u2082S solubility and low crustal copper abundance would restrict Cu/H\u2082S cyanosulfidic networks to specific terrains (e.g., copper-rich, alkaline pools), a critical geochemical constraint on global plausibility. [23]\nFor Strecker chemistry in aqueous-alteration contexts (meteorites or analogous wet-rock systems), the carbonaceous-chondrite analysis emphasizes that ammonia abundance and redox state influence whether aminonitriles (\u2192 amino acids) are favored over cyanohydrins (\u2192 hydroxy acids), and it frames threonine/allothreonine formation as dependent on lactaldehyde availability. [13]\nKey bottlenecks and debates.\nA central unresolved bottleneck is sourcing and sustaining lactaldehyde (and/or its direct nitrile/cyanohydrin precursors) at concentrations compatible with downstream Strecker chemistry. The meteoritic analysis proposes that lactaldehyde may be relatively less available than glycolaldehyde/hydroxyacetone because its formation depends on less abundant ethanol-derived radical chemistry in interstellar ices, which would suppress threonine relative to serine/\u03b1\u2011methylserine\u2014an argument that can be repurposed as a constraint on Earth scenarios if analogous precursor biases held in terrestrial inventories. [13]\nAnother challenge is selectivity and stereochemistry. Multiple experimental contexts support predominantly racemic production for chiral amino acids in abiotic syntheses (e.g., spark discharge products; racemic allo-threonine in some meteoritic extracts where it can be resolved cleanly), but threonine\u2019s second stereocenter makes diastereomeric mixtures (threonine/allothreonine) a near-default outcome unless additional selection mechanisms are invoked. [24]\nA third major issue is compatibility of synthesis with survival. Hydroxy amino acids can undergo dehydration and other transformations during heating or long residence times; this is directly relevant to vent models (where high temperatures can accelerate degradation) and also to post-synthesis processing. [3]\nFinally, there is an ongoing debate over whether threonine should be expected to be among the earliest-abundant amino acids at all. The experimental record shows that threonine is certainly possible abiotically (spark discharge; cyanosulfidic networks yielding its Strecker precursors), but it is also plausibly scarcity-limited by precursor availability (lactaldehyde) and stability constraints (hydroxy amino-acid degradation), leaving room for models where threonine is incorporated later into biochemistry relative to simpler amino acids. [25]\n \n[1] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC426553/\n[2] [6] [8] [25] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4269183/\n[3] https://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\nhttps://pubs.usgs.gov/publication/70012489\n[4] [5] [9] [11] [15] [17] [18] [24] https://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\nhttps://science.gsfc.nasa.gov/sed/content/uploadFiles/publication_files/Parker2011.pdf\n[7] [12] REACTIONS OF AMINOMALONONITRILE WITH ... - HERO\nhttps://hero.epa.gov/reference/10713764/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\n[10] [19] [23] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8240947/\n[13] [14] [16] https://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\nhttps://api.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_download_md/4474944/sci1377.pdf\n[20] [21] https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\nhttps://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1023/A%3A1006668322298.pdf\n[22] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC40511/\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"approved\": <true if any pathway approved>,\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.91,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.95,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.89,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.93,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the strongest pathway and aligns closely with the literature-supported threonine module: HCN-derived cyanide chemistry feeds glycolonitrile, UV/CuCN-H2S photoredox gives glycolaldehyde plus acetaldehyde, acetaldehyde cyanohydrin photoreduction yields lactaldehyde, and lactaldehyde undergoes Strecker conversion to threonine aminonitrile followed by hydrolysis to threonine/allothreonine. The main weakness is that the summary omits explicit mineral/catalyst specification for the surface photoredox steps, which should name CuCN and likely phosphate buffering, and the atmospheric discharge step is simplified. Overall this is a coherent, literature-grounded route to the target.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Explicitly specify CuCN as the photoredox-active mineral/catalyst and H2S as reductant for rxn_005 and rxn_007\",\n        \"Specify phosphate buffer and UV wavelength/holding time for rxn_009 to match the literature more closely\",\n        \"Clarify that rxn_002 produces HCN-rich feedstocks and NH3-bearing species rather than a direct stoichiometric CO2 to HCN/NH3 conversion\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.9,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.93,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.92,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is effectively the same literature-backed cyanosulfidic-Strecker route as P1, framed around direct HCN pool delivery. It is chemically plausible and converges correctly on lactaldehyde and threonine aminonitrile before hydrolysis. It would be stronger if the network explicitly encoded the CuCN/H2S mineral-photoredox context and the realistic multi-step origin of HCN feedstocks.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add explicit surface mineral agents for all surface steps, especially CuCN and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"Represent HCN rainout/accumulation as environmental transfer rather than direct one-step production from CO2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.92,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.91,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.86,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.91,\n      \"feedback\": \"This branch correctly emphasizes the experimentally supported coproduct relationship between glycolonitrile photoreduction and acetaldehyde formation, enabling the acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde sequence. It is strongly aligned with Ritson-Sutherland chemistry. Its weaker point is that environmental sourcing of the initial cyanide and reductant pool is not fully resolved within the pathway itself.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Make the upstream cyanide source explicit within the pathway sequence\",\n        \"State CuCN/H2S/UV conditions directly for the photoreduction steps\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.93,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.74,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"The lactaldehyde-centered Strecker completion module is highly plausible and directly supported by the literature. As a standalone pathway it is incomplete from an origin-of-feedstocks perspective, but as a terminal module inside the full network it is excellent. It clearly reaches the target via a validated aminonitrile intermediate.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Link explicitly to the lactaldehyde-generating photoredox branch\",\n        \"Note that threonine/allothreonine diastereomer formation is expected and literature-consistent\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.76\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.83,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.84,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n      \"feedback\": \"This alternative AMN route is literature-supported in broad outline, but it is less secure than the lactaldehyde Strecker route. AMN formation from HCN oligomerization is plausible, and Thanassi-type electrophile chemistry can produce threonine/allothreonine after hydrolysis. However, the network compresses several steps into a single biochemical reaction and does not fully represent hydrolysis and selectivity issues. Still, it is a reasonable secondary route.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Split AMN addition and hydrolysis into separate reactions to better reflect mechanism\",\n        \"Acknowledge lower selectivity and uncertain geochemical accumulation of AMN\",\n        \"Explicitly show that lactaldehyde still acts as the key electrophile\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.72\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.74,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.76,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n      \"feedback\": \"Direct discharge production of threonine/allothreonine is supported by classic Miller/Ring/Parker literature, so the endpoint is valid. However, the network represents this as an unrealistically compressed reaction from HCN and NH3 directly to threonine/allothreonine. In reality, discharge chemistry proceeds through complex atmospheric radicals, aldehydes, cyanides, and aqueous processing. This pathway is therefore evidence-supported but under-modeled.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_012\",\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Expand direct discharge chemistry into precursor generation plus aqueous assembly steps\",\n        \"Represent aldehydes/ketones and rainout into pools explicitly\",\n        \"Avoid direct stoichiometric shorthand for amino acid formation\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.8,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.92,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.9,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway adds a reasonable hydrothermal feedstock-conditioning front end while preserving the literature-backed surface route. The hydrothermal formate step is plausible as env